{"title_page": "Auto-da-f\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Auto-da-f\u00e9 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Pedro Berruguete Saint Dominic Presiding over an Auto-da-fe 1495.jpg|thumb|[[Saint Dominic]] anachronistically presiding over an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'', by [[Pedro Berruguete]] (around 1495)<ref name=\"Prado\">*[http://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/online-gallery/on-line-gallery/obra/saint-dominic-presides-over-an-auto-da-fe/] at [[Museo del Prado|Prado Museum]]</ref>]]\n\nAn '''''auto-da-f\u00e9''''' (from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] {{lang|pt|auto da f\u00e9}} {{IPA-pt|\u02c8aw.tu d\u0250 \u02c8f\u025b|}}, meaning 'act of faith') was the ritual of public [[penance]] carried out between the 15th and 19th centuries of condemned [[heresy|heretics]] and [[Apostasy|apostates]] imposed by the [[Spanish Inquisition|Spanish]], [[Portuguese Inquisition|Portuguese]], or [[Mexican Inquisition]] as punishment and enforced by civil authorities.  Its most extreme form was [[death by burning]].\n\n==History==\nOn 1 November 1478, [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] and [[Isabella I of Castile]] received permission from [[Pope Sixtus IV]] to name inquisitors throughout their domains in order to protect Catholicism as the one true Christian faith. It originally applied to the [[Crown of Castile]]\u2014the domain of Isabella\u2014but in 1483 Ferdinand extended it to his domain of the [[Crown of Aragon]]. Ferdinand's action met with occasional resistance and resulted in the assassination of the inquisitor [[Pedro de Arbu\u00e9s]] by [[converso|converted Jew]]s in 1485. Despite this, in the following years between 1487 and 1505, the Barcelona chapter recorded processing and trying more than 1,000 heretics, of whom only 25 were ultimately absolved.<ref name=tv3>[http://www.tv3.cat/historiesdecatalunya/cronologia/cron169134131.htm \u00abLa Inquisici\u00f3\u00bb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116184747/http://www.tv3.cat/historiesdecatalunya/cronologia/cron169134131.htm |date=16 November 2011 }}, ''Hist\u00f2ries de Catalunya,'' [[TV3 (Catalonia)|TV3]]'', s.d.</ref>\n\n[[File:History of the great reformation in Europe in the times of Luther and Calvin.. (1870) (14763453874).jpg|thumb|left|upright|An auto-da-f\u00e9 in Seville, illustration from 1870]]\n\nOnce granted permission from the Pope to conduct inquisitions, the monarchs began establishing permanent trials and developing bureaucracies to carry out investigations in most of the cities and communities in their empire. The first [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' took place in [[Seville]] in 1481: the six accused were found guilty and executed.<ref>Cullen Murphy, ''God's Jury: The Inquisition and the Making of the Modern World'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2012, pp. 65-69; {{ISBN|978-0-618-09156-0}}</ref> Later, [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] [[Missionary|missionaries]] brought the [[Inquisition]] to the [[New World]].\n\nThe exact number of people executed by the Inquisition is not known. [[Juan Antonio Llorente]], the ex-secretary of the Holy Office, gave the following numbers for the Inquisition excluding the American colonies, [[Sicily]] and [[Sardinia]]: 31,912 burnt, 17,696 [[Effigy|burned in effigy]], and 291,450 reconciled ''de vehementi'' (i.e., following an act of penance).<ref name=\"Roth1964\">Cecil Roth (1964) The Spanish Inquisition, W. W. Norton & Company, 1964 {{ISBN|0-393-00255-1}}, {{ISBN|978-0-393-00255-3}} page 123</ref> Later in the nineteenth century, [[Jos\u00e9 Amador de los R\u00edos]] gave even higher numbers, stating that between the years 1484 and 1525 alone, 28,540 were burned in person, 16,520 burned in effigy and 303,847 penanced.<ref name=\"Roth1964\"/> However, after extensive examinations of archival records, modern scholars provide lower estimates, indicating that fewer than 10,000 were actually executed during the whole history of the Spanish Inquisition,<ref>Dedieu, p. 85; Perez, pp. 170\u2013173.</ref> perhaps around 3,000.<ref>Monter, p. 53.</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese Inquisition was established in 1536 and lasted officially until 1821. Its influence was much weakened by the late 18th century under the government of the [[Sebasti\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 de Carvalho e Melo, 1st Marquis of Pombal|Marqu\u00eas de Pombal]].\n\n''Autos-da-f\u00e9'' also took place in  [[Goa]] , [[New Spain]], the [[State of Brazil]], and the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRY6rgYan00C&pg=PA215#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Group Identity in the Renaissance World|last=Wojciehowski|first=Hannah Chapelle|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-107-00360-6|location=New York|pages=215\u2013216 with footnotes 98\u2013100}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|last = Marcus\n|first = Jacob Rader\n|authorlink = Jacob Rader Marcus\n|title = The Jew in the Medieval World: A Source Book, 315\u20131791\n|location= Detroit, MI\n|publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]]\n|year = 1999\n|pages = 202\u2013203\n|chapter = 36\n|chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=PCalmtflYtEC&pg=PA202&sig=xmnwzrCJGAwHTzHeFm8fJf7vV_E#PPA202,M1\n|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=PCalmtflYtEC\n|isbn = 0-87820-217-X }}</ref> Contemporary historians of the [[Conquistador]]s, such as [[Bernal D\u00edaz del Castillo]], recorded them.  Although records are incomplete, one historian estimates that about 50 people were executed by the [[Mexican Inquisition]].<ref>Jose Rogelio Alvarez, ed. \"Inquisicion\" (in Spanish). Enciclopedia de Mexico. VII (2000 ed.). Mexico City: Sabeca International Investment Corp.. {{ISBN|1-56409-034-5}}</ref>\n\n== Process ==\n[[File:Francisco rizi-auto de fe.jpg|thumb|left|300px|1683 painting by [[Francisco Rizi]] depicting the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' held in [[Plaza Mayor, Madrid]] in 1680.]]\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was a major aspect of the tribunals,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last= Perry|editor1-first= Mary Elizabeth|editor2-last= Cruz|editor2-first= Anne J.|title= Cultural Encounters: The Impact of the Inquisition in Spain and the New World|year= 1991|publisher=University of California Press|location= Berkeley|isbn= 978-0-520-07098-1}}</ref> and the final step in the [[Spanish Inquisition|Inquisition]] process. It involved a Catholic [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]], prayer, a public procession of those found guilty, and a reading of their sentences.<ref name=\"peters\">Peters, Edward. Inquisition. New York: The Free Press, 1988.</ref>\n\nAn Inquisition usually began with the public proclamation of a grace period of 40 days. Anyone who was guilty or knew of someone who was guilty was urged to confess. If the accused were charged, they were presumed guilty. Officials could apply [[torture]] during the trial. Inquisitors were required to hear and record all testimony.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Proceedings were to be kept secret, and the identity of witnesses was not known to the accused.\n\nAfter the trial, officials proclaimed the prisoner's sentence and administered it in an ''auto-da-f\u00e9''. The ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was not an impromptu event, but thoroughly orchestrated. Preparations began a month in advance and only occurred when the inquisition authorities believed there were enough prisoners in a given community or city. The ritual took place in public squares or esplanades and lasted several hours with ecclesiastical and civil authorities in attendance.<ref>Many of the public ''autos-da-f\u00e9'' were described in contemporary published works listing the dignitaries in attendance, the condemned and their sentences. See, for example, Matias de Bocanegra, ''Auto general de la f\u00e9...'', Mexico: 1649</ref>\n\nBordering the city's plaza, an all-night vigil would be held with prayers, ending in Mass at daybreak and a breakfast feast prepared for all who joined in.<ref>{{cite book|last=Potter|first=Robert|title= The Auto de F\u00e9 as Medieval Drama|location=[[University of California, Santa Barbara]]|pages=110\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Public penitence}}\n\nThe ceremony of public penitence then began with a procession of prisoners, who bore elaborate visual symbols on their garments and bodies. These symbols were called [[sanbenito]], and were made of yellow [[sackcloth]]. They served to identify the specific acts of treason of the accused, whose identities were kept secret until the very last moment. In addition, the prisoners usually had no idea what the outcome of their trial had been or their sentencing.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nThe prisoners were taken outside the city walls to a place called the ''quemadero'' or burning place.  There the sentences were read. Prisoners who were acquitted or whose sentence was suspended would fall on their knees in thanksgiving,<ref>{{cite book|last=Potter|first=Robert|title=The Auto de F\u00e9 as Medieval Drama|location=University of Santa Barbara|pages=115\u2013119}}</ref> but the condemned would be punished. Artistic representations of the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' usually depict physical punishment such as [[flagellation|whipping]], torture, and [[execution by burning|burning at the stake]].\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was also a form of penitence for the public viewers, because they too were engaging in a process of reconciliation and by being involved were given the chance to confront their sins and be forgiven by the Church.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Goya9.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Condemned by the Inquisition wearing a sambenito carrying the cross of St. Andrew  ([[Francisco de Goya]]).]]\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'', usually represented as a heretic being burned at the stake, is a symbol used widely in the arts, especially in Europe.\n\n*[[Voltaire]] featured an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' held by the people of Lisbon after the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake]] in chapter six of his anti-religious satire ''[[Candide]]'' (1759). The university of Coimbra decides that this \"great ceremony was an infallible means of preventing the earth from quaking.\"\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe]] \u2013 In \"[[The Pit and the Pendulum]]\", Poe uses the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' as a reference point for the narrator as he tries to determine what is happening to him.\n*[[Giuseppe Verdi]] \u2013 In his 1866 opera ''[[Don Carlos]]'', Verdi includes a pivotal scene in the third act that depicts the beginning of an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' in front of the Cathedral of Valladolid in Spain where heretics are about to be burned at the stake.\n*[[Herman Melville]] \u2013 In ''[[Moby-Dick]]'', near the end of Chapter 54, mentions ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' in passing: {{\"'}}Though there are no Auto-da-Fe's in Lima now,' said one of the company to another; 'I fear our sailor friend runs the risk of the [[archiepiscopacy]].  Let us withdraw more out of the moonlight.  I see no need of this.{{'\"}} In \"The Confidence-Man: His Masquerade\" (1857), set on a Mississippi steamboat filled with colorful characters and the Devil himself as the con-man, Melville weaves an allegory on how easily one may win over a person's, or for that matter,  an entire people's confidence. The story begins and ends with the appearance of mysterious young men, the latter of whom is described as wearing tattered red and yellow clothes reminiscent of \u201ca victim in <i>auto-da-fe</i>.\u201d The book opens with the words \"Dedicated to victims of Auto da Fe.\"\n*[[Leonard Bernstein]] composed and produced a [[Candide (musical)|musical adaptation of Voltaire's ''Candide'']] in 1956, featuring a song called ''Auto-da-F\u00e9'' that includes the chorus, \"It's a lovely day for drinking and for watching people fry,\" referring to the spectacle of public executions.\n*[[Elias Canetti]] won the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1981 for his work, especially his novel ''Die Blendung'' (1935), literally \"The Blinding,\" translated into English as ''[[Auto-da-F\u00e9 (novel)|Auto-da-F\u00e9]]'' (1946).\n*[[Fyodor Dostoevsky]] begins a chapter of ''[[The Brothers Karamazov]]'' with a \"splendid Auto-da-F\u00e9\". The chapter is famously called \"[[The Grand Inquisitor]]\".\n*In [[Thornton Wilder]]'s 1927 novel [[The Bridge of San Luis Rey]], a central character, the friar Brother Juniper, is burned for heresy in an auto-da-f\u00e9 in early 18th-century [[Peru]].  Although the novel is fictional, autos-de-f\u00e9 did occur in [[Lima, Peru]] at least as late as 1733.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historiayverdad.org/Inquisicion/Auto-de-fe-Lima-Peru-1733.pdf|title=Relacion del auto de fe}}</ref> \n*[[Tennessee Williams]] wrote a one-act play entitled ''Auto-da-F\u00e9'' (1938).\n*[[Roger Zelazny]] wrote a short story, ''[[Auto-da-F\u00e9 (short story)|Auto-da-F\u00e9]]'', which appeared in ''[[Dangerous Visions]]'', 1967.\n*In [[Dai Sijie]]'s ''[[Balzac and the Little Chinese Seamstress]]'', the final climactic book burning is repeatedly referred to as ''auto-da-f\u00e9''.\n*[[Man of La Mancha]], 1965 [[Musical theatre|musical]] with a book by [[Dale Wasserman]].  It tells the story of the \"mad\" knight Don Quixote as a play within a play, performed by Cervantes and his fellow prisoners as he awaits a hearing with the [[Spanish Inquisition]]. \n*[[Richard Zimler]] describes the humiliation and torments of his narrator and an imprisoned [[Jain]] in an auto-da-f\u00e9 in his novel ''Guardian of the Dawn'', which is set in the Portuguese colony of [[Goa]] at the beginning of the 17th century.\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] goes into detail about an Auto-da-f\u00e9 in ''[[Baltasar and Blimunda]]'' (1982).\n*[[Mel Brooks]]'s cult comedy ''[[History of the World, Part I]]'' (1981) makes reference to the auto-da-f\u00e9 in its segment about the [[Spanish Inquisition]].\n*''[[The West Wing]]'' episode \"7A Wf 83429\", the first episode of the fifth season, when referring to a meeting where the Democratic leaders are going to punish them for invoking the 25th, Josh says \"Anyone else coming to the auto da fe?\"\n*[[SPK (band)|SPK]] titled their 1983 compilation album ''Auto Da Fe''.\n*In [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]]'s Gothic novel ''[[The Monk]]'' (1796), [[madrile\u00f1o]] monk Ambrosio barely escapes burning in an auto-da-f\u00e9. Convicted of rape and murder (which also turns out to be incest and matricide) he is sentenced to death by burning at the stake. He is rescued last-minute by the intervention of Lucifer only to be left on a precipice in the [[Sierra Morena]] mountains. After falling down, insects drink his blood and mountain eagles \"tore his flesh piecemeal, and dug out his eye-balls with their crooked beaks\" before he perishes.\n*The 2016 film [[Assassin's Creed (film)|''Assassin's Creed'']] depicts an auto-da-f\u00e9 in 1492 Spain.  The sequence involves a parading of the accused and the outcomes of the sentencing.\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Bibliography\n* Arouet, Francois-Marie (Voltaire) (1758). ''Candide''\n* Dedieu, Jean-Pierre (1987) ''L'Inquisition''. Les Editions Fides\n* Kamen, Henry. (1997) ''The Spanish Inquisition : A Historical Revision''. London: Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n* [[Henry Charles Lea|Lea, Henry Charles]] (1906\u20131907). ''A History of the Inquisition of Spain'' (4 volumes) - [https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi00leah vol.1],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisispain02leah vol.2],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi03leahiala vol.3],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi04leahuoft vol.4]. New York and London.\n* Monter, William (1990). ''Frontiers of Heresy. The Spanish Inquisition from the Basque Land to Sicily''. Cambridge University Press\n* Perez, Joseph (2006) ''The Spanish Inquisition: A History'', Yale University Press. {{ISBN|0-300-11982-8}}, {{ISBN|978-0-300-11982-4}}\n* Peters, Edward. (1988)  ''Inquisition''.  New York: The Free Press.\n* Stavans, Ilan. (2005) ''The Schocken Book of Modern Sephardic Literature''. Random House, Inc. New York\n* Whitechapel, Simon (2003). ''Flesh Inferno: Atrocities of Torquemada and the Spanish Inquisition''. Creation Books. {{ISBN|1-84068-105-5}}\n* ''Miscelanea de Zapata'', Mem. hist\u00f3rico espa\u00f1ol: colecci\u00f3n de documentos, op\u00fasculos y antig\u00fcedades que publica la Real Academia de la Historia (in Spanish, 1851) [https://archive.org/details/memorialhistrico11real/page/202 vol.XI, p.202]\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|auto da fe}}\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.gabrielbernat.es/espana/inquisicion/index.html La Inquisici\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola: origen, desarrollo, organizaci\u00f3n, administraci\u00f3n, m\u00e9todos y proceso inquisitorial]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Auto-da-f\u00e9}}\n{{Italic title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auto-Da-Fe}}\n[[Category:Jewish Portuguese history]]\n[[Category:Jewish Spanish history]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Inquisition]]\n[[Category:Spanish Inquisition]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:History of the conversos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Auto-da-f\u00e9 (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n[[File:Pedro Berruguete Saint Dominic Presiding over an Auto-da-fe 1495.jpg|thumb|[[Saint Dominic]] anachronistically presiding over an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'', by [[Pedro Berruguete]] (around 1495)<ref name=\"Prado\">*[http://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/online-gallery/on-line-gallery/obra/saint-dominic-presides-over-an-auto-da-fe/] at [[Museo del Prado|Prado Museum]]</ref>]]\n\nAn '''''auto-da-f\u00e9''''' (from [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] {{lang|pt|auto da f\u00e9}} {{IPA-pt|\u02c8aw.tu d\u0250 \u02c8f\u025b|}}, meaning 'act of faith') was the ritual of public [[penance]] carried out between the 15th and 19th centuries of condemned [[heresy|heretics]] and [[Apostasy|apostates]] imposed by the [[Spanish Inquisition|Spanish]], [[Portuguese Inquisition|Portuguese]], or [[Mexican Inquisition]] as punishment and enforced by civil authorities.  Its most extreme form was [[death by burning]].\n\n==History==\nOn 1 November 1478, [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] and [[Isabella I of Castile]] received permission from [[Pope Sixtus IV]] to name [[Inquisition|Inquisitors]] throughout their domains to protect [[Catholicism]] as the one true Christian faith. It originally applied to the [[Crown of Castile]]\u2014the domain of Isabella\u2014but in 1483 Ferdinand extended it to his domain of the [[Crown of Aragon]]. Ferdinand's action met with occasional resistance and resulted in the assassination of the inquisitor [[Pedro de Arbu\u00e9s]] by [[converso|converted Jew]]s in 1485. Despite this, in the following years between 1487 and 1505, the Barcelona chapter recorded processing and trying more than 1,000 heretics, of whom only 25 were ultimately absolved.<ref name=tv3>[http://www.tv3.cat/historiesdecatalunya/cronologia/cron169134131.htm \u00abLa Inquisici\u00f3\u00bb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111116184747/http://www.tv3.cat/historiesdecatalunya/cronologia/cron169134131.htm |date=16 November 2011 }}, ''Hist\u00f2ries de Catalunya,'' [[TV3 (Catalonia)|TV3]]'', s.d.</ref>\n\n[[File:History of the great reformation in Europe in the times of Luther and Calvin.. (1870) (14763453874).jpg|thumb|left|upright|An auto-da-f\u00e9 in Seville, illustration from 1870]]\n\nOnce granted permission from the Pope to conduct inquisitions, the monarchs began establishing permanent trials and developing bureaucracies to carry out investigations in most of the cities and communities in their empire. The first [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' took place in [[Seville]] in 1481: the six accused were found guilty and executed.<ref>Cullen Murphy, ''God's Jury: The Inquisition and the Making of the Modern World'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2012, pp. 65-69; {{ISBN|978-0-618-09156-0}}</ref> Later, [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] [[Missionary|missionaries]] brought the [[Inquisition]] to the [[New World]].\n\nThe exact number of people executed by the Inquisition is not known. [[Juan Antonio Llorente]], the ex-secretary of the Holy Office, gave the following numbers for the Inquisition excluding the American colonies, [[Sicily]] and [[Sardinia]]: 31,912 burnt, 17,696 [[Effigy|burned in effigy]], and 291,450 reconciled ''de vehementi'' (i.e., following an act of penance).<ref name=\"Roth1964\">Cecil Roth (1964) The Spanish Inquisition, W. W. Norton & Company, 1964 {{ISBN|0-393-00255-1}}, {{ISBN|978-0-393-00255-3}} page 123</ref> Later in the nineteenth century, [[Jos\u00e9 Amador de los R\u00edos]] gave even higher numbers, stating that between the years 1484 and 1525 alone, 28,540 were burned in person, 16,520 burned in effigy and 303,847 penanced.<ref name=\"Roth1964\"/> However, after extensive examinations of archival records, modern scholars provide lower estimates, indicating that fewer than 10,000 were actually executed during the whole history of the Spanish Inquisition,<ref>Dedieu, p. 85; Perez, pp. 170\u2013173.</ref> perhaps around 3,000.<ref>Monter, p. 53.</ref>\n\nThe Portuguese Inquisition was established in 1536 and lasted officially until 1821. Its influence was much weakened by the late 18th century under the government of the [[Sebasti\u00e3o Jos\u00e9 de Carvalho e Melo, 1st Marquis of Pombal|Marqu\u00eas de Pombal]].\n\n''Autos-da-f\u00e9'' also took place in  [[Goa]] , [[New Spain]], the [[State of Brazil]], and the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRY6rgYan00C&pg=PA215#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Group Identity in the Renaissance World|last=Wojciehowski|first=Hannah Chapelle|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-1-107-00360-6|location=New York|pages=215\u2013216 with footnotes 98\u2013100}}</ref><ref>{{cite book\n|last = Marcus\n|first = Jacob Rader\n|authorlink = Jacob Rader Marcus\n|title = The Jew in the Medieval World: A Source Book, 315\u20131791\n|location= Detroit, MI\n|publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]]\n|year = 1999\n|pages = 202\u2013203\n|chapter = 36\n|chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=PCalmtflYtEC&pg=PA202&sig=xmnwzrCJGAwHTzHeFm8fJf7vV_E#PPA202,M1\n|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=PCalmtflYtEC\n|isbn = 0-87820-217-X }}</ref> Contemporary historians of the [[Conquistador]]s, such as [[Bernal D\u00edaz del Castillo]], recorded them.  Although records are incomplete, one historian estimates that about 50 people were executed by the [[Mexican Inquisition]].<ref>Jose Rogelio Alvarez, ed. \"Inquisicion\" (in Spanish). Enciclopedia de Mexico. VII (2000 ed.). Mexico City: Sabeca International Investment Corp.. {{ISBN|1-56409-034-5}}</ref>\n\n== Process ==\n[[File:Francisco rizi-auto de fe.jpg|thumb|left|300px|1683 painting by [[Francisco Rizi]] depicting the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' held in [[Plaza Mayor, Madrid]] in 1680.]]\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was a major aspect of the tribunals,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last= Perry|editor1-first= Mary Elizabeth|editor2-last= Cruz|editor2-first= Anne J.|title= Cultural Encounters: The Impact of the Inquisition in Spain and the New World|year= 1991|publisher=University of California Press|location= Berkeley|isbn= 978-0-520-07098-1}}</ref> and the final step in the [[Spanish Inquisition|Inquisition]] process. It involved a Catholic [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]], prayer, a public procession of those found guilty, and a reading of their sentences.<ref name=\"peters\">Peters, Edward. Inquisition. New York: The Free Press, 1988.</ref>\n\nAn Inquisition usually began with the public proclamation of a grace period of 40 days. Anyone who was guilty or knew of someone who was guilty was urged to confess. If the accused were charged, they were presumed guilty. Officials could apply [[torture]] during the trial. Inquisitors were required to hear and record all testimony.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} Proceedings were to be kept secret, and the identity of witnesses was not known to the accused.\n\nAfter the trial, officials proclaimed the prisoner's sentence and administered it in an ''auto-da-f\u00e9''. The ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was not an impromptu event, but thoroughly orchestrated. Preparations began a month in advance and only occurred when the inquisition authorities believed there were enough prisoners in a given community or city. The ritual took place in public squares or esplanades and lasted several hours with ecclesiastical and civil authorities in attendance.<ref>Many of the public ''autos-da-f\u00e9'' were described in contemporary published works listing the dignitaries in attendance, the condemned and their sentences. See, for example, Matias de Bocanegra, ''Auto general de la f\u00e9...'', Mexico: 1649</ref>\n\nBordering the city's plaza, an all-night vigil would be held with prayers, ending in Mass at daybreak and a breakfast feast prepared for all who joined in.<ref>{{cite book|last=Potter|first=Robert|title= The Auto de F\u00e9 as Medieval Drama|location=[[University of California, Santa Barbara]]|pages=110\u2013115}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|Public penitence}}\n\nThe ceremony of public penitence then began with a procession of prisoners, who bore elaborate visual symbols on their garments and bodies. These symbols were called [[sanbenito]], and were made of yellow [[sackcloth]]. They served to identify the specific acts of treason of the accused, whose identities were kept secret until the very last moment. In addition, the prisoners usually had no idea what the outcome of their trial had been or their sentencing.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nThe prisoners were taken outside the city walls to a place called the ''quemadero'' or burning place.  There the sentences were read. Prisoners who were acquitted or whose sentence was suspended would fall on their knees in thanksgiving,<ref>{{cite book|last=Potter|first=Robert|title=The Auto de F\u00e9 as Medieval Drama|location=University of Santa Barbara|pages=115\u2013119}}</ref> but the condemned would be punished. Artistic representations of the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' usually depict physical punishment such as [[flagellation|whipping]], torture, and [[execution by burning|burning at the stake]].\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' was also a form of penitence for the public viewers, because they too were engaging in a process of reconciliation and by being involved were given the chance to confront their sins and be forgiven by the Church.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Goya9.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Condemned by the Inquisition wearing a sambenito carrying the cross of St. Andrew  ([[Francisco de Goya]]).]]\n\nThe ''auto-da-f\u00e9'', usually represented as a heretic being burned at the stake, is a symbol used widely in the arts, especially in Europe.\n\n*[[Voltaire]] featured an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' held by the people of Lisbon after the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake]] in chapter six of his anti-religious satire ''[[Candide]]'' (1759). The university of Coimbra decides that this \"great ceremony was an infallible means of preventing the earth from quaking.\"\n*[[Edgar Allan Poe]] \u2013 In \"[[The Pit and the Pendulum]]\", Poe uses the ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' as a reference point for the narrator as he tries to determine what is happening to him.\n*[[Giuseppe Verdi]] \u2013 In his 1866 opera ''[[Don Carlos]]'', Verdi includes a pivotal scene in the third act that depicts the beginning of an ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' in front of the Cathedral of Valladolid in Spain where heretics are about to be burned at the stake.\n*[[Herman Melville]] \u2013 In ''[[Moby-Dick]]'', near the end of Chapter 54, mentions ''auto-da-f\u00e9'' in passing: {{\"'}}Though there are no Auto-da-Fe's in Lima now,' said one of the company to another; 'I fear our sailor friend runs the risk of the [[archiepiscopacy]].  Let us withdraw more out of the moonlight.  I see no need of this.{{'\"}} In \"The Confidence-Man: His Masquerade\" (1857), set on a Mississippi steamboat filled with colorful characters and the Devil himself as the con-man, Melville weaves an allegory on how easily one may win over a person's, or for that matter,  an entire people's confidence. The story begins and ends with the appearance of mysterious young men, the latter of whom is described as wearing tattered red and yellow clothes reminiscent of \u201ca victim in <i>auto-da-fe</i>.\u201d The book opens with the words \"Dedicated to victims of Auto da Fe.\"\n*[[Leonard Bernstein]] composed and produced a [[Candide (musical)|musical adaptation of Voltaire's ''Candide'']] in 1956, featuring a song called ''Auto-da-F\u00e9'' that includes the chorus, \"It's a lovely day for drinking and for watching people fry,\" referring to the spectacle of public executions.\n*[[Elias Canetti]] won the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1981 for his work, especially his novel ''Die Blendung'' (1935), literally \"The Blinding,\" translated into English as ''[[Auto-da-F\u00e9 (novel)|Auto-da-F\u00e9]]'' (1946).\n*[[Fyodor Dostoevsky]] begins a chapter of ''[[The Brothers Karamazov]]'' with a \"splendid Auto-da-F\u00e9\". The chapter is famously called \"[[The Grand Inquisitor]]\".\n*In [[Thornton Wilder]]'s 1927 novel [[The Bridge of San Luis Rey]], a central character, the friar Brother Juniper, is burned for heresy in an auto-da-f\u00e9 in early 18th-century [[Peru]].  Although the novel is fictional, autos-de-f\u00e9 did occur in [[Lima, Peru]] at least as late as 1733.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historiayverdad.org/Inquisicion/Auto-de-fe-Lima-Peru-1733.pdf|title=Relacion del auto de fe}}</ref> \n*[[Tennessee Williams]] wrote a one-act play entitled ''Auto-da-F\u00e9'' (1938).\n*[[Roger Zelazny]] wrote a short story, ''[[Auto-da-F\u00e9 (short story)|Auto-da-F\u00e9]]'', which appeared in ''[[Dangerous Visions]]'', 1967.\n*In [[Dai Sijie]]'s ''[[Balzac and the Little Chinese Seamstress]]'', the final climactic book burning is repeatedly referred to as ''auto-da-f\u00e9''.\n*[[Man of La Mancha]], 1965 [[Musical theatre|musical]] with a book by [[Dale Wasserman]].  It tells the story of the \"mad\" knight Don Quixote as a play within a play, performed by Cervantes and his fellow prisoners as he awaits a hearing with the [[Spanish Inquisition]]. \n*[[Richard Zimler]] describes the humiliation and torments of his narrator and an imprisoned [[Jain]] in an auto-da-f\u00e9 in his novel ''Guardian of the Dawn'', which is set in the Portuguese colony of [[Goa]] at the beginning of the 17th century.\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] goes into detail about an Auto-da-f\u00e9 in ''[[Baltasar and Blimunda]]'' (1982).\n*[[Mel Brooks]]'s cult comedy ''[[History of the World, Part I]]'' (1981) makes reference to the auto-da-f\u00e9 in its segment about the [[Spanish Inquisition]].\n*''[[The West Wing]]'' episode \"7A Wf 83429\", the first episode of the fifth season, when referring to a meeting where the Democratic leaders are going to punish them for invoking the 25th, Josh says \"Anyone else coming to the auto da fe?\"\n*[[SPK (band)|SPK]] titled their 1983 compilation album ''Auto Da Fe''.\n*In [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]]'s Gothic novel ''[[The Monk]]'' (1796), [[madrile\u00f1o]] monk Ambrosio barely escapes burning in an auto-da-f\u00e9. Convicted of rape and murder (which also turns out to be incest and matricide) he is sentenced to death by burning at the stake. He is rescued last-minute by the intervention of Lucifer only to be left on a precipice in the [[Sierra Morena]] mountains. After falling down, insects drink his blood and mountain eagles \"tore his flesh piecemeal, and dug out his eye-balls with their crooked beaks\" before he perishes.\n*The 2016 film [[Assassin's Creed (film)|''Assassin's Creed'']] depicts an auto-da-f\u00e9 in 1492 Spain.  The sequence involves a parading of the accused and the outcomes of the sentencing.\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Bibliography\n* Arouet, Francois-Marie (Voltaire) (1758). ''Candide''\n* Dedieu, Jean-Pierre (1987) ''L'Inquisition''. Les Editions Fides\n* Kamen, Henry. (1997) ''The Spanish Inquisition : A Historical Revision''. London: Weidenfeld & Nicolson.\n* [[Henry Charles Lea|Lea, Henry Charles]] (1906\u20131907). ''A History of the Inquisition of Spain'' (4 volumes) - [https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi00leah vol.1],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisispain02leah vol.2],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi03leahiala vol.3],[https://archive.org/details/historyofinquisi04leahuoft vol.4]. New York and London.\n* Monter, William (1990). ''Frontiers of Heresy. The Spanish Inquisition from the Basque Land to Sicily''. Cambridge University Press\n* Perez, Joseph (2006) ''The Spanish Inquisition: A History'', Yale University Press. {{ISBN|0-300-11982-8}}, {{ISBN|978-0-300-11982-4}}\n* Peters, Edward. (1988)  ''Inquisition''.  New York: The Free Press.\n* Stavans, Ilan. (2005) ''The Schocken Book of Modern Sephardic Literature''. Random House, Inc. New York\n* Whitechapel, Simon (2003). ''Flesh Inferno: Atrocities of Torquemada and the Spanish Inquisition''. Creation Books. {{ISBN|1-84068-105-5}}\n* ''Miscelanea de Zapata'', Mem. hist\u00f3rico espa\u00f1ol: colecci\u00f3n de documentos, op\u00fasculos y antig\u00fcedades que publica la Real Academia de la Historia (in Spanish, 1851) [https://archive.org/details/memorialhistrico11real/page/202 vol.XI, p.202]\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|auto da fe}}\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.gabrielbernat.es/espana/inquisicion/index.html La Inquisici\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola: origen, desarrollo, organizaci\u00f3n, administraci\u00f3n, m\u00e9todos y proceso inquisitorial]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Auto-da-f\u00e9}}\n{{Italic title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Auto-Da-Fe}}\n[[Category:Jewish Portuguese history]]\n[[Category:Jewish Spanish history]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Inquisition]]\n[[Category:Spanish Inquisition]]\n[[Category:Christian terminology]]\n[[Category:History of the conversos]]\n", "name_user": "A loose necktie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auto-da-f%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Black Salt Collective", "text_new": "'''Black Salt Collective''' is an American [[queer]], women-of-color artist collective<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soex.org/black-salt-collective|title=Black Salt Collective|date=2014-04-11|work=Southern Exposure|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref> that currently consists of four [[California]]-based artists and curators: [[Sarah Biscarra-Dilley]], [[Grace Rosario Perkins]], Anna Luisa Petrisko, and Adee Roberson.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Artists-carving-out-space-for-women-of-color-in-6762743.php|title=Artists carving out space for women of color in art world|last=Kost|first=Ryan|date=2016-01-15|work=SFGate|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> Founded in 2012, Black Salt Collective's art practice crosses disciplines and media, including performance, [[video]], installation, [[Sound recording and reproduction|sound]], [[painting]], [[collage]], [[Textile|textiles]], [[sculpture]], and [[printmaking]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nFounding member Anna Luisa Petrisko has explained that, among other commonalities, the group's members \"all make artwork with the intention of healing. Healing ourselves, healing our communities, healing the past and healing the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelesigh.com/2013/07/collective-black-salt.html|title=Collective: Black Salt|website=www.thelesigh.com|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> The group is known for expanding narratives of art practice and [[art history]] beyond male, Eurocentric points of view.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/29169/1/the-art-collective-reimagining-the-past-and-future-for-woc|title=The art collective reimagining the past and future for WOC|last=Dazed|date=2016-01-14|work=Dazed|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs an artist collective, Black Salt Collective has exhibited at [[Artists' Television Access|Artists\u2019 Television Access]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atasite.org/2013/03/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective \u2013 Artists' Television Access|website=www.atasite.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browntourage.com/magazine/black-salt-collective-ft-jeepneys-at-ata-gallery/|title=BLACK SALT COLLECTIVE FT. JEEPNEYS at ATA Gallery|date=2013-03-09|work=BROWNTOURAGE MOVED TO BROWNTOURAGE.COM|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> the [[San Francisco Public Library]] (as part of the Radar Reading Series),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpl.org/?pg=1014109001|title=*Radar Reading Series|website=SFPL|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> MIX Festival, [[The Outsider Festival|Outsider Festival]], and Glitch Festival Australia.<ref name=\"openengagement.info\">{{Cite web|url=http://openengagement.info/speaker/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective {{!}} Open Engagement|website=openengagement.info|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> In 2016 Black Salt Collective participated in the Artist in Residence Program at Facebook.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kqed.org/arts/13689222/women-to-watch-black-salt-collective|title=Women to Watch: Black Salt Collective|last=Hotchkiss|first=Sarah|date=Jul 20, 2017|website=KQED|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As a curatorial collective, Black Salt Collective has held a curatorial residency at SOMArts (2016) resulting in the [[exhibition]] \"Visions into Infinite Archives.\"<ref name=\"somarts.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|title=Black Salt Collective\u2019s Visions Into Infinite Archives \u2014 SOMArts|website=www.somarts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328022257/http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> They have spoken at the Open Engagement conference (2016),<ref name=\"openengagement.info\"/> the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|title=Spring 2016 Arts Colloquium: Black Salt Collective  {{!}} UCSB College of Creative Studies|website=www.ccs.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328021008/https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Occidental College]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxy.edu/events/oxy-arts-speaker-series-black-salt-collective|title=Oxy Arts Speaker Series: Black Salt Collective {{!}} Occidental College {{!}} The Liberal Arts College in Los Angeles|website=www.oxy.edu|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Projects and exhibitions ==\n\n===''Visions Into Infinite Archives''===\nBlack Salt Collective's curatorial residency opened in January 2016 in SOMArt\u2019s Main Gallery with the exhibition \u201cVisions into Infinite Archives.\u201d featured 30 artists and [[Filmmaking|filmmakers]] of color.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/01/14/black-salt-collective-agitates-the-archive-with-visions-at-somarts/|title=Black Salt Collective Agitates the Archive with \u2018Visions\u2019 at SOMArts|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"somarts.org\"/> The exhibition has been described as \"energetically showcas[ing] a wide spectrum of artists of color engaging in equally varied disciplinary and conceptual approaches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://temporaryartreview.com/visions-into-infinite-archives-at-somarts/|title=Visions Into Infinite Archives at SOMArts {{!}} Temporary Art Review|website=temporaryartreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> while also \" putting elements of their ancestry in dialogue with their lived experiences through inventive [[Juxtaposition|juxtapositions]], many offering visions of [[Utopia|utopian]] futures.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/visions-into-infinite-archives-resists-the-neat-tidy-and-eurocentric/Content?oid=4655539|title='Visions into Infinite Archives' Resists the Neat, Tidy, and Eurocentric|last=Voynovskaya|first=Nastia|website=East Bay Express|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===''Space and Place''===\nA [[multimedia]] exhibition featuring images and video of the Black Salt Collective members singing and dancing in the confines of a room.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sactownmag.com/The-Weekender/2018/Sacramento-Museum-Day/|title=Explore these 10 museums and cultural centers for free on Sacramento Museum Day|last=Chao|first=Vu|date=2018-01-31|work=SacTown magazine|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> This was shown at the [[Verge Center for the Arts]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:American artist groups and collectives]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American arts organizations]]\n", "text_old": "'''Black Salt Collective''' is an American [[queer]], women-of-color artist collective<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.soex.org/black-salt-collective|title=Black Salt Collective|date=2014-04-11|work=Southern Exposure|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref> that currently consists of four [[California]]-based artists and curators: [[Sarah Biscarra-Dilley]], [[Grace Rosario Perkins]], Anna Luisa Petrisko, and Adee Roberson.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/art/article/Artists-carving-out-space-for-women-of-color-in-6762743.php|title=Artists carving out space for women of color in art world|last=Kost|first=Ryan|date=2016-01-15|work=SFGate|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> Founded in 2012, Black Salt Collective's art practice crosses disciplines and media, including performance, [[video]], installation, [[Sound recording and reproduction|sound]], [[painting]], [[collage]], [[Textile|textiles]], [[sculpture]], and [[printmaking]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nFounding member Anna Luisa Petrisko has explained that, among other commonalities, the group's members \"all make artwork with the intention of healing. Healing ourselves, healing our communities, healing the past and healing the future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelesigh.com/2013/07/collective-black-salt.html|title=Collective: Black Salt|website=www.thelesigh.com|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> The group is known for expanding narratives of art practice and [[art history]] beyond male, Eurocentric points of view.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/29169/1/the-art-collective-reimagining-the-past-and-future-for-woc|title=The art collective reimagining the past and future for WOC|last=Dazed|date=2016-01-14|work=Dazed|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs an artist collective, Black Salt Collective has exhibited at [[Artists' Television Access|Artists\u2019 Television Access]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atasite.org/2013/03/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective \u2013 Artists' Television Access|website=www.atasite.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.browntourage.com/magazine/black-salt-collective-ft-jeepneys-at-ata-gallery/|title=BLACK SALT COLLECTIVE FT. JEEPNEYS at ATA Gallery|date=2013-03-09|work=BROWNTOURAGE MOVED TO BROWNTOURAGE.COM|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-US}}</ref> the [[San Francisco Public Library]] (as part of the Radar Reading Series),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpl.org/?pg=1014109001|title=*Radar Reading Series|website=SFPL|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> MIX Festival, [[The Outsider Festival|Outsider Festival]], and Glitch Festival Australia.<ref name=\"openengagement.info\">{{Cite web|url=http://openengagement.info/speaker/black-salt-collective/|title=Black Salt Collective {{!}} Open Engagement|website=openengagement.info|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> As a curatorial collective, Black Salt Collective has held a curatorial residency at SOMArts (2016) resulting in the [[exhibition]] \"Visions into Infinite Archives.\"<ref name=\"somarts.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|title=Black Salt Collective\u2019s Visions Into Infinite Archives \u2014 SOMArts|website=www.somarts.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328022257/http://www.somarts.org/infinitearchives/|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> They have spoken at the Open Engagement conference (2016),<ref name=\"openengagement.info\"/> the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|title=Spring 2016 Arts Colloquium: Black Salt Collective  {{!}} UCSB College of Creative Studies|website=www.ccs.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328021008/https://www.ccs.ucsb.edu/news-and-events/events/spring-2016-arts-colloquium-black-salt-collective|archive-date=2017-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Occidental College]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxy.edu/events/oxy-arts-speaker-series-black-salt-collective|title=Oxy Arts Speaker Series: Black Salt Collective {{!}} Occidental College {{!}} The Liberal Arts College in Los Angeles|website=www.oxy.edu|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== Projects and exhibitions ==\n\n===''Visions Into Infinite Archives''===\nBlack Salt Collective's curatorial residency opened in January 2016 in SOMArt\u2019s Main Gallery with the exhibition \u201cVisions into Infinite Archives.\u201d featured 30 artists and [[Filmmaking|filmmakers]] of color.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/01/14/black-salt-collective-agitates-the-archive-with-visions-at-somarts/|title=Black Salt Collective Agitates the Archive with \u2018Visions\u2019 at SOMArts|work=KQED Arts|access-date=2017-03-12|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\"somarts.org\"/> The exhibition has been described as \"energetically showcas[ing] a wide spectrum of artists of color engaging in equally varied disciplinary and conceptual approaches\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://temporaryartreview.com/visions-into-infinite-archives-at-somarts/|title=Visions Into Infinite Archives at SOMArts {{!}} Temporary Art Review|website=temporaryartreview.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref> while also \" putting elements of their ancestry in dialogue with their lived experiences through inventive [[Juxtaposition|juxtapositions]], many offering visions of [[Utopia|utopian]] futures.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/visions-into-infinite-archives-resists-the-neat-tidy-and-eurocentric/Content?oid=4655539|title='Visions into Infinite Archives' Resists the Neat, Tidy, and Eurocentric|last=Voynovskaya|first=Nastia|website=East Bay Express|access-date=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===''Space and Place''===\nA [[multimedia]] exhibition featuring images and video of the Black Salt Collective members singing and dancing in the confines of a room.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sactownmag.com/The-Weekender/2018/Sacramento-Museum-Day/|title=Explore these 10 museums and cultural centers for free on Sacramento Museum Day|last=Chao|first=Vu|date=2018-01-31|work=SacTown magazine|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref> This was shown at the [[Verge Center for the Arts]] in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] in 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Artists from California]]\n[[Category:American artist groups and collectives]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from the United States]]\n[[Category:African-American arts organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Hammyburgy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Facebook AIR info", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Salt_Collective"}
{"title_page": "G\u00f6tz Werner", "text_new": "[[File:Goetz-werner-centralstation-da-24-03-2010-009.jpg|thumb|G\u00f6tz W. Werner]]\n\n'''G\u00f6tz Wolfgang Werner''' (born 5 February 1944 in [[Heidelberg]]) is the founder, co-owner, and member of the [[advisory board]] of [[dm-drogerie markt]], a [[Germany|German]] [[drugstore]] chain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.basic-income.net/downloads/Werner.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723023013/http://www.basic-income.net/downloads/Werner.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the company for 35 years. From October 2003 till September 2010, he was the head of the Cross-Department Group for Entrepreneurial Studies at the [[Karlsruhe Institute of Technology]].\n\nBased in [[Rudolf Steiner]]'s teachings of [[Anthroposophy]], G\u00f6tz Werner is one of the most influential advocates of [[basic income]] in Germany (''1000&nbsp;Euros for everyone''<ref>{{YouTube|NrWTE0yeVo8|G\u00f6tz Werner - 1000 Euro f\u00fcr Jeden (Freiheit Gleichheit Grundeinkommen)}}</ref>). He founded the initiative ''Unternimm die Zukunft'', or ''Become an entrepreneur of the future''.<ref>[http://www.unternimm-die-zukunft.de/ unternimm-die-zukunft.de]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Einkommen f\u00fcr alle. Der dm-Chef \u00fcber die Machbarkeit des bedingungslosen Grundeinkommens.'' Kiepenheuer & Witsch, K\u00f6ln 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-462-03775-3}}.\n* with Adrienne Goehler: ''1000 \u20ac f\u00fcr jeden. Freiheit, Gleichheit, Grundeinkommen.'' Econ, Berlin 2010, {{ISBN|978-3-430-20108-7}}.\n* with Claudia Cornelson: ''Womit ich nie gerechnet habe. Die Autobiographie'', Berlin: Ullstein 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-430-20153-7}}.\n* with Peter Dellbr\u00fcgger (Hrsg.): ''Wozu F\u00fchrung? Dimensionen einer Kunst.'' KIT Scientific Publishing, Karlsruhe 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7315-0116-9}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unternimm-die-zukunft.de/de/goetz-werner/ G\u00f6tz Werner] on the ''Unternimm die Zukunft'' website (in German)\n\n{{Basic income}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Werner, Gotz}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:Anthroposophists]]\n[[Category:Basic income in Germany]]\n[[Category:Basic income activists]]\n[[Category:German businesspeople]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Heidelberg]]\n[[Category:People from the Republic of Baden]]\n\n\n{{Germany-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Goetz-werner-centralstation-da-24-03-2010-009.jpg|thumb|G\u00f6tz W. Werner]]\n\n'''G\u00f6tz Wolfgang Werner''' (born 5 February 1944 in [[Heidelberg]]) is the founder, co-owner, and member of the [[advisory board]] of [[dm-drogerie markt]], a [[Germany|German]] [[drugstore]] chain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.basic-income.net/downloads/Werner.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723023013/http://www.basic-income.net/downloads/Werner.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He led the company for 35 years. From October 2003 till September 2010, he was the head of the Cross-Department Group for Entrepreneurial Studies at the [[Karlsruhe Institute of Technology]].\n\nBased in [[Rudolf Steiner]]'s teachings of [[Anthroposophy]], G\u00f6tz Werner is one of the most influential advocates of [[basic income]] in Germany (''1000&nbsp;Euros for everyone''<ref>{{YouTube|NrWTE0yeVo8|G\u00f6tz Werner - 1000 Euro f\u00fcr Jeden (Freiheit Gleichheit Grundeinkommen)}}</ref>). He founded the initiative ''Unternimm die Zukunft'', or ''Become an entrepreneur of the future''.<ref>[http://www.unternimm-die-zukunft.de/ unternimm-die-zukunft.de]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Einkommen f\u00fcr alle. Der dm-Chef \u00fcber die Machbarkeit des bedingungslosen Grundeinkommens.'' Kiepenheuer & Witsch, K\u00f6ln 2007, {{ISBN|978-3-462-03775-3}}.\n* with Adrienne Goehler: ''1000 \u20ac f\u00fcr jeden. Freiheit, Gleichheit, Grundeinkommen.'' Econ, Berlin 2010, {{ISBN|978-3-430-20108-7}}.\n* with Claudia Cornelson: ''Womit ich nie gerechnet habe. Die Autobiographie'', Berlin: Ullstein 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-430-20153-7}}.\n* with Peter Dellbr\u00fcgger (Hrsg.): ''Wozu F\u00fchrung? Dimensionen einer Kunst.'' KIT Scientific Publishing, Karlsruhe 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7315-0116-9}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.unternimm-die-zukunft.de/de/goetz-werner/ G\u00f6tz Werner] on the ''Unternimm die Zukunft'' website (in German)\n\n{{Basic income}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Werner, Gotz}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Anthroposophists]]\n[[Category:Basic income in Germany]]\n[[Category:Basic income activists]]\n[[Category:German businesspeople]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Heidelberg]]\n[[Category:People from the Republic of Baden]]\n\n\n{{Germany-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6tz_Werner"}
{"title_page": "9 PM (Till I Come)", "text_new": "{{short description|1998 single by ATB}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = 9 PM (Till I Come)\n| cover      = 9 PM (Till I Come) cover.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[ATB]]\n| album      = [[Movin' Melodies]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1998}}\n| format     =\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[12-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=19}}\n| label      =\n*[[Kontor Records|Kontor]] (Germany)\n*[[Radikal Records|Radikal]] (U.S.)\n| writer     = [[ATB|Andr\u00e9 Tanneberger]]\n| producer   = Andr\u00e9 Tanneberger\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Don't Stop! (ATB song)|Don't Stop!]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = ATB 9pm (Till I Come).ogg\n | description = Six-second sample which highlights the pitch-bent guitar sound that is ATB's trademark\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''9 PM (Till I Come)'''\" is a song by German [[electronic dance music]] producer [[Andr\u00e9 Tanneberger|ATB]], featuring vocals by Yolanda Rivera released as his debut single and the lead single from his debut album ''[[Movin' Melodies]]'' (1999).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=7788|title=9 P.M. (Till I Come) by ATB Songfacts|accessdate=28 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" peaked at number 14 on the [[German Singles Chart]]. Internationally, the song was also successful. The single entered at number one in the [[United Kingdom]] for the week ending 3 July 1999, and stayed there for two weeks,<ref name=\"uk\"/> becoming the country's fifth best-selling single of 1999.<ref name=\"ukye\"/> As of July 2014, it has sold over 890,000 copies in the UK.<ref name=\"uksales\"/> The song was also number one in the [[Republic of Ireland]] for four consecutive weeks. It reached number three in Denmark, Italy and Norway, number five in [[Flanders]] and number ten in Australia.\n\n==Track listings==\n{{col-begin|width=74%}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (Amir Sattarpour Release_Iran Release)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:14\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Club Mix) \u2013 5:25\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (9 PM Mix) \u2013 6:07\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Sequential One Remix) \u2013 6:09\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Gary D's Northern Light Remix) \u2013 7:29\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Spacekid Remix) \u2013 6:40\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Signum Remix) \u2013 7:34\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (Germany Release 1)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:19\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Club Mix) \u2013 5:25\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (9 PM Mix) 6:10\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (Germany Release 2)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:14\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Club Mix) \u2013 5:25\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (9 PM Mix) \u2013 6:07\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Sequential One Remix) \u2013 6:09\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Gary D's Northern Light Remix) \u2013 7:29\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Spacekid Remix) \u2013 6:40\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (The UK Mixes) (Germany Release)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Mix UK) \u2013 2:43\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Signum Remix) \u2013 7:33\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Sequential One 1999 Remix) \u2013 6:24\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (U.S. Release)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Mix) \u2013 3:16\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Club Mix) \u2013 5:27\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Sequential One Remix) \u2013 6:09\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Gary D's Northern Light Remix) \u2013 7:26\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Signum Remix) \u2013 7:33\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (UK Release 1)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:14\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Club Mix) \u2013 5:25\n{{col-2}}\n\n*'''9 PM (Till I Come) (UK Release 2)'''\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 2:43\n#\"9 PM (Till I Come)\" (Sequential One 1999 Remix) \u2013 6:26\n