{"title_page": "Wolfgang Schreyer", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Wolfgang Schreyer\n| birth_name    = \n| image     = Wolfgang Schreyer (2004) by Guenter Prust.jpg\n| caption      = Wolfgang Schreyer (2004)\n| imagesize     = \n| birth_date     = 20 November 1927\n| birth_place    = [[Magdeburg]], [[Province of Saxony]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2017|11|14|1927|11|20|df=y}}\n| death_place    =  [[Ahrenshoop]]\n| occupation    = Writer\n|party         = [[NSDAP]] (1944\u20131945)\n|partner        = \n|children        = \n|parents    = \n|alma_mater =\n| nationality   = Germany\n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-37039-0004, Verleihung des Heinrich-Mann-Preis an Franz F\u00fchmann.jpg|thumb|Wolfgang Schreyer (left) with [[Franz F\u00fchmann]] and [[Rudolf Fischer (writer)|Rudolf Fischer]].]]\n'''Wolfgang Schreyer''' (20 November 1927 &ndash; 14 November 2017) was a German writer of fiction, historic adventures mixed with documentary, science fiction for TV shows and movies and is best known as the author of over 20 adventure stories.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWS>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=3156|author1=[[Bernd-Rainer Barth]]|author2=|title=Schreyer, Wolfgang * 20.11.1927 Schriftsteller|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken |accessdate= 31 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nWolfgang Schreyer was born the son of a [[pharmacist]].   On leaving secondary school he was conscripted as a [[Flakhelfer]] before, in April 1944, he joined the [[Nazi Party]] and served in the [[Wehrmacht]]. He became a [[POW]] and was released by the Americans in 1946. From 1947 until 1949 he was a chemists' apprentice, working in that profession until 1950. From 1950 to 1952 he was the manager of a pharmaceutical company in the [[German Democratic Republic]].\n\nSince the publication of his first crime novel, \"Gro\u00dfgarage S\u00fcdwest\" he worked as a freelance author. He travelled several times to the [[Caribbean]] and to the United States. Since 1958, the GDR's [[Ministerium f\u00fcr Staatssicherheit|Staatssicherheitsdienst (Stasi)]] kept him under special surveillance. Until 1972 Schreyer lived in [[Magdeburg]]; since then he lived in [[Ahrenshoop]] on the coast of the Baltic Sea.\n\nSchreyer was the author of numerous novels, which are mainly considered entertainment, containing some criticism of society. Most successful were the stories set in Central America and the Caribbean, in which he skillfully mixed fiction and documentary. Other works are crime stories, a science-fiction story, film scripts, TV and radio drama. Having sold more than five million copies, Schreyer is considered one of the most successful East German authors.\n\nIn 1956 Schreyer was awarded the [[Heinrich-Mann-Preis]]. Since 1952 he was a member of the East German authors guild, since 1974 a member of [[P.E.N.]]; and since [[German reunification]] in 1990 he was a member of the German authors guild.\n\nSchreyer died on 14 November 2017 at the age of 89.<ref>[http://www.ndr.de/nachrichten/mecklenburg-vorpommern/DDR-Autor-Wolfgang-Schreyer-gestorben,schreyer104.html DDR-Autor Wolfgang Schreyer gestorben] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n* ''Gro\u00dfgarage S\u00fcdwest'', Berlin 1952\n* ''Mit Kr\u00e4uterschnaps und Gottvertrauen'', Berlin 1953\n* ''Unternehmen \"Thunderstorm\"'', Berlin 1954\n* ''Die Banknote'', Berlin 1955\n* ''Sch\u00fcsse \u00fcber der Ostsee'', Berlin 1956\n* ''Der Traum des Hauptmann Loy'', Berlin 1956\n* ''Das Attentat'', Berlin 1957\n* ''Der Spion von Akrotiri'', Berlin 1957\n* ''Alaskaf\u00fcchse'', Berlin 1959\n* ''Das gr\u00fcne Ungeheuer'', Berlin 1959\n* ''Entscheidung an der Weichsel'', Berlin 1960\n* ''Tempel des Satans'', Berlin 1960\n* ''Die Piratenchronik'', Berlin 1961 (republished in 1967 as ''Augen am Himmel: Eine Piratenchronik'' (Eyes in the sky))\n* ''Vampire, Tyrannen, Rebellen'', Berlin 1963 (together with G\u00fcnter Schumacher)\n* ''Preludio 11'', Berlin 1964\n* ''Fremder im Paradies'', Halle (Saale) 1966 (republished 1971 within ''Welt der Abenteuer'')\n* ''Aufstand des Sisyphos'', Berlin 1969 (together with J\u00fcrgen Hell)\n* ''Der gelbe Hai'', Berlin 1969\n* ''Bananengangster'', Berlin 1970\n* ''Der Adjutant'', Halle (S.) 1971\n* ''Der Resident'', Halle (Saale) 1973\n* ''Tod des Chefs oder Die Liebe zur Opposition'', Berlin 1975\n* ''Schwarzer Dezember'', Halle (Saale) 1977\n* ''Die Entf\u00fchrung'', Halle [u.a.] 1979\n* ''Der Reporter'', Halle [u.a.] 1980\n* ''Die Suche oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Berlin 1981\n* ''Eiskalt im Paradies'', Halle [u.a.] 1982\n* ''Die f\u00fcnf Leben des Dr. Gundlach'', Berlin 1982\n* ''Der Fund oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Berlin 1987\n* ''Der Mann auf den Klippen'', Berlin 1987\n* ''Der sechste Sinn'', Halle [u.a.] 1987\n* ''Unabwendbar'', Berlin 1988\n* ''Die Beute'', Rostock 1989\n* ''Endzeit der Sieger'', Halle [u.a.] 1989\n* ''Alptr\u00e4ume'', Oschersleben 1991\n* ''Nebel'', Berlin 1991\n* ''Das Quartett'', Berlin 1994\n* ''Der zweite Mann'', Berlin 2000\n* ''Der Verlust oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Rostock 2001\n* ''Das Kurhaus'', Rostock 2002\n* ''Die Legende'', Berlin 2006 (together with Paul Schreyer)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{DNB portal|122338820|TYP=}}\n* [http://www.stiftung-aufarbeitung.de/service_wegweiser/personen_detail.php?ID=2184 Profile] at [[Stiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur]]\n* [http://www.mvweb.de/kdb/autoren/schreyer/ Profil at mvweb.de]\n* http://www.dielegende.info/\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20120213134430/http://www.ila-bonn.de/buchbesprechungen/buecher249.htm\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schreyer, Wolfgang}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Magdeburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Nazi Party members]]\n[[Category:East German writers]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Saxony-Anhalt]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German prisoners of war in World War II held by the United States]]\n[[Category:Heinrich Mann Prize winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Wolfgang Schreyer\n| birth_name    = \n| image     = Wolfgang Schreyer (2004) by Guenter Prust.jpg\n| caption      = Wolfgang Schreyer (2004)\n| imagesize     = \n| birth_date     = 20 November 1927\n| birth_place    = [[Magdeburg]], [[Province of Saxony]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2017|11|14|1927|11|20|df=y}}\n| death_place    =  [[Ahrenshoop]]\n| occupation    = Writer\n|party         = [[NSDAP]] (1944\u20131945)\n|partner        = \n|children        = \n|parents    = \n|alma_mater =\n| nationality   = Germany\n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-37039-0004, Verleihung des Heinrich-Mann-Preis an Franz F\u00fchmann.jpg|thumb|Wolfgang Schreyer (left) with [[Franz F\u00fchmann]] and [[Rudolf Fischer (writer)|Rudolf Fischer]].]]\n'''Wolfgang Schreyer''' (20 November 1927 &ndash; 14 November 2017) was a German writer of fiction, historic adventures mixed with documentary, science fiction for TV shows and movies and is best known as the author of over 20 adventure stories.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenWS>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=3156|author1=[[Bernd-Rainer Barth]]|author2=|title=Schreyer, Wolfgang * 20.11.1927 Schriftsteller|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken |accessdate= 31 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nWolfgang Schreyer was born the son of a [[pharmacist]].   On leaving secondary school he was conscripted as a [[Flakhelfer]] before, in April 1944, he joined the [[Nazi Party]] and served in the [[Wehrmacht]]. He became a [[POW]] and was released by the Americans in 1946. From 1947 until 1949 he was a chemists' apprentice, working in that profession until 1950. From 1950 to 1952 he was the manager of a pharmaceutical company in the [[German Democratic Republic]].\n\nSince the publication of his first crime novel, \"Gro\u00dfgarage S\u00fcdwest\" he worked as a freelance author. He travelled several times to the [[Caribbean]] and to the United States. Since 1958, the GDR's [[Ministerium f\u00fcr Staatssicherheit|Staatssicherheitsdienst (Stasi)]] kept him under special surveillance. Until 1972 Schreyer lived in [[Magdeburg]]; since then he lived in [[Ahrenshoop]] on the coast of the Baltic Sea.\n\nSchreyer was the author of numerous novels, which are mainly considered entertainment, containing some criticism of society. Most successful were the stories set in Central America and the Caribbean, in which he skillfully mixed fiction and documentary. Other works are crime stories, a science-fiction story, film scripts, TV and radio drama. Having sold more than five million copies, Schreyer is considered one of the most successful East German authors.\n\nIn 1956 Schreyer was awarded the [[Heinrich-Mann-Preis]]. Since 1952 he was a member of the East German authors guild, since 1974 a member of [[P.E.N.]]; and since [[German reunification]] in 1990 he was a member of the German authors guild.\n\nSchreyer died on 14 November 2017 at the age of 89.<ref>[http://www.ndr.de/nachrichten/mecklenburg-vorpommern/DDR-Autor-Wolfgang-Schreyer-gestorben,schreyer104.html DDR-Autor Wolfgang Schreyer gestorben] {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\n* ''Gro\u00dfgarage S\u00fcdwest'', Berlin 1952\n* ''Mit Kr\u00e4uterschnaps und Gottvertrauen'', Berlin 1953\n* ''Unternehmen \"Thunderstorm\"'', Berlin 1954\n* ''Die Banknote'', Berlin 1955\n* ''Sch\u00fcsse \u00fcber der Ostsee'', Berlin 1956\n* ''Der Traum des Hauptmann Loy'', Berlin 1956\n* ''Das Attentat'', Berlin 1957\n* ''Der Spion von Akrotiri'', Berlin 1957\n* ''Alaskaf\u00fcchse'', Berlin 1959\n* ''Das gr\u00fcne Ungeheuer'', Berlin 1959\n* ''Entscheidung an der Weichsel'', Berlin 1960\n* ''Tempel des Satans'', Berlin 1960\n* ''Die Piratenchronik'', Berlin 1961 (republished in 1967 as ''Augen am Himmel: Eine Piratenchronik'' (Eyes in the sky))\n* ''Vampire, Tyrannen, Rebellen'', Berlin 1963 (together with G\u00fcnter Schumacher)\n* ''Preludio 11'', Berlin 1964\n* ''Fremder im Paradies'', Halle (Saale) 1966 (republished 1971 within ''Welt der Abenteuer'')\n* ''Aufstand des Sisyphos'', Berlin 1969 (together with J\u00fcrgen Hell)\n* ''Der gelbe Hai'', Berlin 1969\n* ''Bananengangster'', Berlin 1970\n* ''Der Adjutant'', Halle (S.) 1971\n* ''Der Resident'', Halle (Saale) 1973\n* ''Tod des Chefs oder Die Liebe zur Opposition'', Berlin 1975\n* ''Schwarzer Dezember'', Halle (Saale) 1977\n* ''Die Entf\u00fchrung'', Halle [u.a.] 1979\n* ''Der Reporter'', Halle [u.a.] 1980\n* ''Die Suche oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Berlin 1981\n* ''Eiskalt im Paradies'', Halle [u.a.] 1982\n* ''Die f\u00fcnf Leben des Dr. Gundlach'', Berlin 1982\n* ''Der Fund oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Berlin 1987\n* ''Der Mann auf den Klippen'', Berlin 1987\n* ''Der sechste Sinn'', Halle [u.a.] 1987\n* ''Unabwendbar'', Berlin 1988\n* ''Die Beute'', Rostock 1989\n* ''Endzeit der Sieger'', Halle [u.a.] 1989\n* ''Alptr\u00e4ume'', Oschersleben 1991\n* ''Nebel'', Berlin 1991\n* ''Das Quartett'', Berlin 1994\n* ''Der zweite Mann'', Berlin 2000\n* ''Der Verlust oder Die Abenteuer des Uwe Reuss'', Rostock 2001\n* ''Das Kurhaus'', Rostock 2002\n* ''Die Legende'', Berlin 2006 (together with Paul Schreyer)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{DNB portal|122338820|TYP=}}\n* [http://www.stiftung-aufarbeitung.de/service_wegweiser/personen_detail.php?ID=2184 Profile] at [[Stiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur]]\n* [http://www.mvweb.de/kdb/autoren/schreyer/ Profil at mvweb.de]\n* http://www.dielegende.info/\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20120213134430/http://www.ila-bonn.de/buchbesprechungen/buecher249.htm\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schreyer, Wolfgang}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Magdeburg]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Nazi Party members]]\n[[Category:East German writers]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Saxony-Anhalt]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:German prisoners of war in World War II held by the United States]]\n[[Category:Heinrich Mann Prize winners]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfgang_Schreyer"}
{"title_page": "Wolf Wondratschek", "text_new": "[[File:Wolf Wondratschek 2003 2.jpg|thumb|Wolf Wondratschek, 2003]]\n'''Wolf Wondratschek''' (born August 14, 1943) is a German [[author]]. He was born in [[Rudolstadt]] in [[Thuringia]].\n\n==Life==\nWondratschek grew up in [[Karlsruhe]]. From 1962 through 1967, he studied [[literature]], [[philosophy]] and [[sociology]] at the [[Ruprecht Karl University of Heidelberg]], [[Georg-August University of G\u00f6ttingen]], and the [[Johann Wolfgang Goethe University of Frankfurt am Main]]. In 1968, Wolf won the prestigious Leonce and Lena Prize for poetry given by the city of [[Darmstadt]].<ref>{{Citation|last = Spaeth|first = Becker|title = Preistr\u00e4ger|publisher = Literarischer M\u00e4rz|year = 2013|url = http://www.literarischer-maerz.de/preistraeger.php|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> The next year, Wolf's first book, ''[[Fr\u00fcher begann der Tag mit einer Schu\u00dfwunde]]'', came out to critical acclaim;<ref>{{Cite book|last= Wondratschek|first= Wolf|title= Fr\u00fcher begann der Tag mit einer Schu\u00dfwunde|year= 1969|publisher= Carl Hanser|location= Munich|language = German|asin= B0000BU9DZ}}</ref> the short stories which included his famous piece, ''[[Mittagspause]]''. During 1970 and 1971, Wolf was a Research Fellow at the [[University of Warwick]].<ref>{{cite book|last = Wondratschek|first = Wolf|title = Omnibus|publisher = Carl Hanser|year = 1972|location = Munich|language = German}}</ref> In 1970, he won the [[H\u00f6rspielpreis der Kriegsblinden]] for his [[radio play]] ''[[Paul oder die Zerst\u00f6rung]]'' (''Paul or the Destruction'').<ref>{{Citation|title = H\u00f6rspielpreis der Kriegsblinden|publisher = Bund der Kriegsblinden Deutschlands e.V.|year = 2012|url = http://www.kriegsblindenbund.de/cms/hoerspielpreis-der-kriegsblinden.html|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> He continued to publish both poetry and prose during the 1980s, when he took an extended vacation to the United States, and Mexico. Upon his return to Germany, Wondratschek settled into residences in Munich and Vienna, publishing not only poetry and prose, but also radio plays and screenplays. In 2012, Wolf was awarded the [[Literaturpreis der Wilhelm und Christine Hirschmann-Stiftung]], a [[Bavaria]]n literary prize.<ref>{{Citation|title = 20.000 Euro f\u00fcr den Dichter Wolf Wondratschek|publisher = Der Standard|date = 27 September 2011 |url = http://derstandard.at/1317018585891/Hirschmann-Stiftung-20000-Euro-fuer-den-Dichter-Wolf-Wondratschek|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nWondratschek was influenced mainly by writers from [[Gruppe 47]], such as [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] and [[Paul Celan]]. His work is characterized by its sparseness and usage of \"colloquial language; his sentences are short and clear, grammatically reduced to a minimum.\"<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last = Moeller|editor-first = Jack|title = Wolf Wondratschek|publisher = Houghton Mifflin|series = Kaleidoskop|year = 1991|location = Boston}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Violanta (film)|Violanta]]'' (1976)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wondratschek, Wolf}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rudolstadt]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Thuringia]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wolf Wondratschek 2003 2.jpg|thumb|Wolf Wondratschek, 2003]]\n'''Wolf Wondratschek''' (born August 14, 1943) is a German [[author]]. He was born in [[Rudolstadt]] in [[Thuringia]].\n\n==Life==\nWondratschek grew up in [[Karlsruhe]]. From 1962 through 1967, he studied [[literature]], [[philosophy]] and [[sociology]] at the [[Ruprecht Karl University of Heidelberg]], [[Georg-August University of G\u00f6ttingen]], and the [[Johann Wolfgang Goethe University of Frankfurt am Main]]. In 1968, Wolf won the prestigious Leonce and Lena Prize for poetry given by the city of [[Darmstadt]].<ref>{{Citation|last = Spaeth|first = Becker|title = Preistr\u00e4ger|publisher = Literarischer M\u00e4rz|year = 2013|url = http://www.literarischer-maerz.de/preistraeger.php|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> The next year, Wolf's first book, ''[[Fr\u00fcher begann der Tag mit einer Schu\u00dfwunde]]'', came out to critical acclaim;<ref>{{Cite book|last= Wondratschek|first= Wolf|title= Fr\u00fcher begann der Tag mit einer Schu\u00dfwunde|year= 1969|publisher= Carl Hanser|location= Munich|language = German|asin= B0000BU9DZ}}</ref> the short stories which included his famous piece, ''[[Mittagspause]]''. During 1970 and 1971, Wolf was a Research Fellow at the [[University of Warwick]].<ref>{{cite book|last = Wondratschek|first = Wolf|title = Omnibus|publisher = Carl Hanser|year = 1972|location = Munich|language = German}}</ref> In 1970, he won the [[H\u00f6rspielpreis der Kriegsblinden]] for his [[radio play]] ''[[Paul oder die Zerst\u00f6rung]]'' (''Paul or the Destruction'').<ref>{{Citation|title = H\u00f6rspielpreis der Kriegsblinden|publisher = Bund der Kriegsblinden Deutschlands e.V.|year = 2012|url = http://www.kriegsblindenbund.de/cms/hoerspielpreis-der-kriegsblinden.html|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> He continued to publish both poetry and prose during the 1980s, when he took an extended vacation to the United States, and Mexico. Upon his return to Germany, Wondratschek settled into residences in Munich and Vienna, publishing not only poetry and prose, but also radio plays and screenplays. In 2012, Wolf was awarded the [[Literaturpreis der Wilhelm und Christine Hirschmann-Stiftung]], a [[Bavaria]]n literary prize.<ref>{{Citation|title = 20.000 Euro f\u00fcr den Dichter Wolf Wondratschek|publisher = Der Standard|date = 27 September 2011 |url = http://derstandard.at/1317018585891/Hirschmann-Stiftung-20000-Euro-fuer-den-Dichter-Wolf-Wondratschek|accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nWondratschek was influenced mainly by writers from [[Gruppe 47]], such as [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] and [[Paul Celan]]. His work is characterized by its sparseness and usage of \"colloquial language; his sentences are short and clear, grammatically reduced to a minimum.\"<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last = Moeller|editor-first = Jack|title = Wolf Wondratschek|publisher = Houghton Mifflin|series = Kaleidoskop|year = 1991|location = Boston}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''[[Violanta (film)|Violanta]]'' (1976)\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wondratschek, Wolf}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rudolstadt]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from Thuringia]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolf_Wondratschek"}
{"title_page": "Wieland F\u00f6rster", "text_new": "[[File:W. F\u00f6rster.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|'''Wieland F\u00f6rster '''}}<br>{{right| ''Ilona Ripke, 2010''}}]]\n[[File:OdF-Denkmal2.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Victims of Fascism memorial at Freital-D\u00f6hlen}}]]\n[[File:Gro\u00dfe Badende.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Great bather}}]]\n[[File:Chemnitz Stadthallenpark F\u00f6rster Wissenschaft 3.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Scholarship (Chemnitz)}}]]\n[[File:Heinrich boell.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Heinrich B\u00f6ll (Prenzlauer Berg, Berlin)}}]]\n[[File:L\u00fcttenort - Wieland F\u00f6rster (Hemdausziehende II 1963) 2 2015-03-17.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Removing shirt }}]]\n'''Wieland F\u00f6rster''' (born 12 February 1930) is a [[Germany|German]] sculptor, artist and writer.<ref name=WFlautSAK>{{cite web|title=Wieland F\u00f6rster|url=http://www.sadk.de/foerster.html|work=Klasse Bildende Kunst| publisher=S\u00e4chsische Akademie der K\u00fcnste, Dresden|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=WFlautwww>{{cite web| title=F\u00f6rster, Wieland   * 12.2.1930   Bildhauer, Grafiker, Schriftsteller| url=https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3b-1424.html?ID=853| work=\"Wer war wer in der DDR?\"| author1=Anke Scharnhorst|author2=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]| publisher=Ch. Links Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>  A recurring theme of his work is victimhood, reflecting his own youthful experiences during the [[Bombing of Dresden|incineration of Dresden]] in February 1945 and of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] justice system between 1946 and 1950.<ref name=WFlautDLR>{{cite web|title=\"In mir blutet Vergangenheit\"|author1=Carola Wiemers|author2=Michael Opitz|url= http://www.deutschlandradiokultur.de/wieland-foerster-in-mir-blutet-vergangenheit.976.de.html?dram:article_id=309566| date=13 February 2015|publisher= Deutschlandradio (DLR Kultur), K\u00f6ln|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis life has been documented in unusual detail, not least by himself.   By 2015 it was reported that the daily diary which he has kept since 1953 had reached its 150th unpublished \"volume\".<ref name=WFlautDLR/>\n\n== Life ==\n=== Childhood and youth ===\nWieland F\u00f6rster was born, the youngest of his parents' four children, in [[:de:Laubegast|Laubegast]], a suburb of [[Dresden]].   His father was employed in the transport and commercial sectors.<ref name=WFlautwww/>    In 1935 his father died as a result of wounds sustained during the [[First World War]], leaving his mother to raise the children under conditions of financial hardship.  She succeeded in distancing them from Nazi indoctrination.   As a school boy, between 1936 and 1944, Wieland rejected the Nazi system and pressures to take part in government sponsored uniformed organisations.   In 1944 he took an apprenticeship as a trainee technical draftsman at the Dresden municipal waterworks.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch|title=Biografie|work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA10| year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9| pages=9\u201317}}</ref>   Towards the end of 1944, still aged only 14, he was sent for four weeks to a [[Hitler Youth]] detention camp.  On his release he volunteered for [[:de:Organisation freiwilliger Luftschutzhelfer|fire-watch duties]] in order to avoid further unwelcome interruptions to his training and education.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL>{{cite web|url=http://das-blaettchen.de/2016/10/franz-fuehmanns-und-wieland-foersters-briefwechsel-37590.html|title=Franz F\u00fchmanns und Wieland F\u00f6rsters Briefwechsel (book review)|date=10 October 2016|author=Peter Liebers|publisher= Das Bl\u00e4ttchen, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt is reported that he was such a quick learner as an apprentice technical draftsmen that after a year he was \"promoted\" to a preparatory year for a degree course at the Engineering Academy.   He was also conscripted into the local branch of the newly launched [[Volkssturm|German Home Guard (''\"Volksturm\"'')]], and it was as a member of the Home Guard that he experienced the [[Bombing of Dresden|English and American air attacks that destroyed the central districts of city]] one day after his fifteenth birthday, on the night of 13 February 1945.<ref name=WFlautDLR/>   In the chaos following the attacks he was able to escape from the Home Guard, remaining in his home district till war ended, formally on 8 May 1945, after which Dresden and the surrounding region of central Germany were [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|administered]] as the [[Soviet occupation]].   Technical draftsmanship was officially designated as women's work, and Wieland was required to undertake hands-on work (''\"als Rohrleger\"'') in industrial engineering.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL/>\n\nOn 17 September 1946 he found himself taken in by the police and handed over to the [[NKVD]] after a neighbour denounced him on grounds of suspected possession of weapons.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL/>    The background to the affair was an attempt to make the F\u00f6rster family exchange their home for rented accommodation, after the German police had blocked an attempt by the Communist authorities to make them pay rent for living in their own home.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   Wieland was initially sentenced to ten years of forced labour in [[Siberia]], but after three months of nightly interrogation, a Soviet military tribunal reduced the term to 7\u00bd years.   On 28 December 1946 he was interned at [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]], a concentration camp which the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|authorities]] had constructed  next to [[:de:Justizvollzugsanstalt Bautzen|the jail]] at [[Bautzen]].   As the camp commanders set about sorting out the prisoners fit for work to be transported to Siberia, a Soviet military doctor determined that Wieland F\u00f6rster was unfit for work.   He was therefore left behind in [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]].<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In the aftermath of war the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|authorities]] refused to discuss or even to acknowledge the continuing existence of concentration camps in the [[Soviet occupation zone|Soviet part]] of occupied Germany, but their all too physical presence never became increasingly hard to dispute.   By 1950 F\u00f6rster was in poor general health dangerously ill with [[Tuberculosis]] and on 21 January 1950, following a threatened investigation by the [[International Red Cross]], he was the beneficiary of a \"backdoor\" release, emerging from the camp without identity papers and without any formal pardon or other explanation.   Official acknowledgment that he had been a victim of Stalinist persecution followed in 1991.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\n=== Further study and training===\nDespite having emerged from after nearly four years interned in [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]], in 1950 F\u00f6rster was still aged only 20.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   The previous year, in October 1949, the [[Soviet occupation zone]] had been relaunched as the Soviet sponsored [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (East Germany)]].   It was in this new kind of [[one-party state|one-]][[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] [[National Front (East Germany)|dictatorship]],  with its principal [[Constitution of East Germany|political]] and economic structures modelled on those of the [[Soviet Union]] itself, that F\u00f6rster built his life and career over the next four decades.   He abandoned his ambition to become a technical draftsman, but nevertheless returned to work with the Dresden municipal waterworks, employed in the planning department till 1953.<ref name=WFlautGH>{{cite web|url=http://www.galerie-himmel.de/en/Kuenstler/Wieland-Foerster/Vita_2_2.html|title=Wieland F\u00f6rster|publisher=Galerie Himmel, Dresden|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>   During these years he was using his spare time to try out various artistic forms of expression, such as writing, music, theatre and advertising, along with the more visual arts.   In the Autumn/Fall of 1952 he took part in a public \"drawing event\" at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]] where the teachers encouraged him to enroll as a student.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nHe applied to his employers to back his application to sponsor his application to study at [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts|the academy]], but was turned down for reasons that involved the risk of \"Verb\u00fcrgerlichung\" (''loosely: \"bourgeoisization\"'').   He therefore made the application anyway, on his own responsibility, and was accepted.   He was a student at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]] between 1953 and 1958.<ref name=WFlautwww/>   He began his study of sculpting in 1953, taught by [[Walter Arnold (sculptor)|Walter Arnold]] and Arnold's assistant [[Gerd Jaeger]] .   Another of his teachers was [[Hans Steger (sculptor)|Hans Steger]].   The focus of the training at Dresden was on [[:de:Neoklassizismus (Bildende Kunst)|neoclassical form]], backed up by compulsory courses in drawing, on use of plaster casts and on nature.   The study of anatomy and history of art were also included and required.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nBy his second year F\u00f6rster was already establishing contacts with representatives of the officially forbidden \"classical modern\" art movement.   By this time the [[Iron curtain|division]] [[Allied-occupied Germany|of Germany]] agreed between the [[Allies of World War II|Americans and the Soviets]] at [[Yalta Conference|Yalta]] at the beginning of 1945 had crystallised into  a permanent frontier, but the [[Inner German border|border]] between the two Germanies was still relatively porous, especially between [[West Berlin]] and the surrounding territories governed as [[East Germany]], and F\u00f6rster took the opportunity to visit [[Bernhard Heiliger]] in [[West Berlin|the west]].   [[Walter Arnold (sculptor)|Walter Arnold]], himself a consummate hands-on craftsman, helped a few of his students, whom he regarded as politically reliable, to deepen their understanding on the essential elements in figurative sculpture, by gaining experience with the works of the westerners [[Hermann Haller (sculptor)|Hermann Haller]] and [[Charles Despiau]].<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In his third year, required to produce a \"portrait from a 'photo\", F\u00f6rster chose as his subject [[Bertolt Brecht]], a long-standing icon of the German intellectual left but nevertheless at this stage ostracised by [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|the authorities]].   In order to accomplish his course objective he was permitted, a few weeks before [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht's]] death in 1956, to attend a rehearsal of [[Life of Galileo]], being staged by the [[Berliner Ensemble|Berliner Ensemble (theatre company)]].<ref name=WFlautZZ>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeitzeugen-tv.com/dossier/movie/4220/wieland-foerster-ein-stiller-rebell.html| title=Wieland F\u00f6rster. Ein stiller Rebell. |publisher=Zeitzeugen Lizenzmanagement (haftungsbeschr\u00e4nkt) UG, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe received his degree in 1958 he applied for a three-year Master Course at the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|Arts Academy in East Berlin]], hoping to study with [[Gustav Seitz]].   However, it was becoming progressively more impractical for Seitz to sustain a life-style that involved pursuing a career simultaneously in [[West German|West]] and [[East Germany]], and 1958 was the year in which he opted to base himself in [[Hamburg]] (in the west).  In order to be able to remain in Berlin, and following the recommendation of Seitz, F\u00f6rster now hesitantly but successfully applied to become a Master Student (''\"Meistersch\u00fcler\"'') with [[Fritz Cremer]].<ref name=WFlautMS>{{cite web |author=Maren Schibilski |url=http://www.rbb-online.de/theodor/archiv/20160619_1832/foerster.html |title=Stiller Rebell - der Bildhauer Wieland F\u00f6rster  |date=19 June 2016 |publisher=Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg (rbb) |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter just eighteen months his time as a Master Student of [[Fritz Cremer|Cremer]] was prematurely terminated in connection with the increasingly heated debate then emerging on the subject of [[Formalism (art)|Formalism]].   He was permitted to use a workshop at the academy to complete his Life-sized plus group of figures \"V\u00f6lkerfreundschaft unter Studenten\" (literally ''\"People's friendship between students\"'') which won the [[TU Dresden]] prize in 1961/62.<ref name=\"Mlekusch201202\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch|title=Wettbewerbe und Auftraege|work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA75| year=2012| publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9|pages=75\u201384}}</ref>\n\n=== Retreat and recovery ===\nIn 1961 Wieland F\u00f6rster set himself up in a Berlin shop building which became his studio.   For some years he lived and worked here as a virtual hermit, visited by his family and a couple of close friends, notably {{Interlanguage link multi|Erich Arendt|de}} and [[Franz F\u00fchmann]].   The authorities did not endorse his self-imposed exile but nor, at least initially, do they appear to have interfered.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   His only child, Eva F\u00f6rster, was born in Berlin's [[Prenzlauer Berg]] quarter in 1968.   From the time she was six years old her father insisted that she should keep a daily diary, a habit through which she developed a succinct writing style:  she grew up to become a theatre critic, writer and lyricist-poet.<ref name=EFlautSF>{{cite web|url=http://www.eva-foerster.de/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/moz2012.pdf?iframe=true&width=950&height=700|title=Eingefangene Gef\u00fchlsst\u00fcrme:  Keine Eskapaden, keine Skandale \u2013 die Berliner Lyrikerin Eva F\u00f6rster \u00fcber die Arbeit an ihren Gedichten, \u00fcber ihre Inspirationen und Ansichten vom aufregenden Alltagsleben |author=Silvia Fichtner|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>   Between 1968 and 1972, the authorities became disruptive.   F\u00f6rster  was banned from exhibiting his works between 1968 and 1973,<ref name=WFlautwww/> and he was subjected to surveillance techniques that became increasingly intrusive.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In the absence of membership of the government approved professional association it became hard to obtain materials, and for some time he operated without an official tax payer reference number.   His perceived attitude in the great [[Formalism (art)|Formalism]] debate and his artistic style earned official condemnation.   In the end, in December 1972, working under conditions of increasing privation from which his health suffered, he was able to arrange an evidently candid meeting with [[Konrad Wolf]], the politically well connected president of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], at which he spelled out his situation.    The timing was propitious, in that the country's new leader, [[Erich Honecker]], was cautiously trying to move the East German government beyond the unrelenting inflexibility of [[Walter Ulbricht|his predecessor]].   The exhibitions ban was lifted, and  F\u00f6rster found himself elected to membership of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]].   More generally, from now on, till the [[Die Wende|demise]] of the East German state in 1989/90, he became a (semi-detached and unconventional) member of the artistic establishment: his relationship with the state now reflected a certain level of mutual acceptance bordering on respect.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nBetween 1979 and 1990 he served as fifth vice-president, with responsibility for the training of Master Students (''\"Meistersch\u00fcler\"'') at the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]].   In 1985 he was appointed to a professorship.   Since 1991 he has also been a member of [[PEN Centre Germany]].   However, 1991 was also the year in which he resigned from the (formerly ''East'' German) National Arts Academy in protest at the inadequacy of the institution's willingness to investigate and disclose its role under the East German dictatorship.<ref name=WFlautwww/>  Following [[German reunification|reunification]], in 1991 he was obliged to relocate from his 16 M<small>2</small> studio to a small back yard which is where, despite by now suffering from serious heart disease, much of his later work was produced.   For his larger sandstone sculptures he used a piece of land he had acquired (and where he still lives) at [[:de:Wensickendorf|Wensickendorf]] near [[Oranienburg]], to the north of Berlin.<ref name=WFinWensickendorf>{{cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Oberhavel/Luther-in-Oranienburg|title=Luther in Oranienburg ... Im Oranienburger Amtshauptmannshaus, hat die Stadt zu Ehren von Wieland F\u00f6rster ein Zimmer eingerichtet. Im Schloss selber gab es keinen ad\u00e4quaten Raum, so B\u00fcrgermeister Hans-Joachim Laesicke.|author=Fritz-Herrmann K\u00f6ser|date=27 April 2014|publisher=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine (MAZ)|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992<ref name=WFlautGH/><!---There are LOTS of google hits for sites giving this 1992 date, but to my jaundiced eye they all look as though they might very well have been lifted from wikipedia.   And several of the more trusted sites where I would not be surprised to see this mentioned do not, in fact, show it.  So I THINK I prefer 2010 which comes from an entry on the academy's website.   Not able to be 100% certain either way, however.---> or 2010 the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]] took over the Wieland F\u00f6rster Archive, comprising many pages his correspondence with fellow artists and with the authorities in East Germany.<ref name=WFArchiv>{{cite web|date=26 May 2010|title=Akademie der K\u00fcnste erh\u00e4lt das Archiv von Wieland F\u00f6rster| publisher=Akademie der K\u00fcnste |url=http://www.adk.de/de/presse/?we_objectID=25243|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>   In 1996 he was a founding member of the [[S\u00e4chsische Akademie der K\u00fcnste|Saxony Arts Academy]] in [[Dresden]],<ref name=WFlautwww/> to which in 2001 he agreed to donate 58 sculptures.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\n== Output ==\nF\u00f6rster was producing lithographic work from 1960.   His first etchings and sculptures for public spaces appeared in 1962.   During the years that followed he took several working trips abroad.   His 1967 stay in [[Tunisia]] was particularly important in influencing his later work.<ref name=\"Mlekusch201203\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch| title=Vaterlandsschaftung| work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA37|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9|pages=37\u201347}}</ref>   However, foreign travel was a privilege rather than a right, and between 1968 and 1973 governmental agencies imposed various ideologically based blockages including the ban on exhibiting.   Grudging rehabilitation, backed by [[Konrad Wolf]], followed in 1974, when he was admitted to the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], and he was almost immediately able to stage his first major exhibition (organised by {{Interlanguage link multi|Rudolf Tsch\u00e4pe|de}}) in [[Potsdam]] in the former observatory building on the [[Telegrafenberg|Telegraph Hill]].<ref name=RTlautlautBLPB>{{cite web|url=https://www.politische-bildung-brandenburg.de/node/7798|title=Rudolf Tsch\u00e4pe - Ein Portr\u00e4t|date=9 December 2011|work= Pr\u00e4sentation der Videodokumentation auf der Fassade der Gedenkst\u00e4tte Lindenstra\u00dfe 54/55 f\u00fcr die Opfer politischer Gewalt im 20. Jahrhundert |publisher=Dr. Martina Weyrauch i.A. Brandenburgische Landeszentrale f\u00fcr politische Bildung| accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nWieland F\u00f6rster still works as a visual artist.   Additionally, since the 1970s he has published a series of books and articles reflecting aspects of his own artistic creations.<ref name=DNBumWF>{{cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&query=118534173|title=Literatur von und \u00fcber Wieland F\u00f6rster|work=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek |publisher=Deutsche Nationalbibliothek, Frankfurt am Main | accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n''not necessarily a complete list''\n* 1966: [[Will Lammert Prize]] of the German Arts Academy, Berlin\n* 1973: [[Kunstpreis der DDR]]\n* 1974: [[K\u00e4the Kollwitz Prize]] of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], Berlin\n* 1976: [[National Prize of the German Democratic Republic]] for arts and literature, 3rd class\n* 1977: Kleist Arts City Prize from [[Frankfurt (Oder)]]\n* 1978: [[:de:Kunstpreis des FDGB|Arts Prize of the Trades Union Confederation]] \n* 1983: [[National Prize of the German Democratic Republic]] for arts and literature, 2nd class\n* 1996: [[:de:Kunstpreis der Landeshauptstadt Dresden|Arts Prize of the Saxon capital, Dresden]]\n* 2000: [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] 1st class\n* 2009: [[:de:Brandenburgischer Kunstpreis|Brandenburg Arts Prize]] for life's achievement\n* 2010: Honorary doctorate from the Faculty of Philosophy [[Universit\u00e4t Potsdam]]\n* 2012: [[Order of Merit of Brandenburg]]\n\n<!---\n\nIn Bautzen schwor er sich, angesichts der enormen Todesrate zumeist unschuldiger H\u00e4ftlinge, diesen Opfern politischer Willk\u00fcr, in welcher Form auch immer, durch Mahnung und Gedenken ein Weiterleben zu sichern, was er in k\u00fcnstlerischer Form umsetzen wollte.[2] [according to wiki-DE this comes from pages 10-11 of \"source \"Mlekusch2012\" but I can't find it.   Need to look more closely.   It's a nice quote for some purposes.]\n\n--->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:F\u00f6rster, Wieland}}\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:East German artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German printmakers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:Victims of human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Prize of East Germany]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:W. F\u00f6rster.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|'''Wieland F\u00f6rster '''}}<br>{{right| ''Ilona Ripke, 2010''}}]]\n[[File:OdF-Denkmal2.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Victims of Fascism memorial at Freital-D\u00f6hlen}}]]\n[[File:Gro\u00dfe Badende.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Great bather}}]]\n[[File:Chemnitz Stadthallenpark F\u00f6rster Wissenschaft 3.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Scholarship (Chemnitz)}}]]\n[[File:Heinrich boell.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Heinrich B\u00f6ll (Prenzlauer Berg, Berlin)}}]]\n[[File:L\u00fcttenort - Wieland F\u00f6rster (Hemdausziehende II 1963) 2 2015-03-17.jpg|right|thumb|300px|{{center|Removing shirt }}]]\n'''Wieland F\u00f6rster''' (born 12 February 1930) is a [[Germany|German]] sculptor, artist and writer.<ref name=WFlautSAK>{{cite web|title=Wieland F\u00f6rster|url=http://www.sadk.de/foerster.html|work=Klasse Bildende Kunst| publisher=S\u00e4chsische Akademie der K\u00fcnste, Dresden|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=WFlautwww>{{cite web| title=F\u00f6rster, Wieland   * 12.2.1930   Bildhauer, Grafiker, Schriftsteller| url=https://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3b-1424.html?ID=853| work=\"Wer war wer in der DDR?\"| author1=Anke Scharnhorst|author2=[[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]]| publisher=Ch. Links Verlag, Berlin & Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>  A recurring theme of his work is victimhood, reflecting his own youthful experiences during the [[Bombing of Dresden|incineration of Dresden]] in February 1945 and of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] justice system between 1946 and 1950.<ref name=WFlautDLR>{{cite web|title=\"In mir blutet Vergangenheit\"|author1=Carola Wiemers|author2=Michael Opitz|url= http://www.deutschlandradiokultur.de/wieland-foerster-in-mir-blutet-vergangenheit.976.de.html?dram:article_id=309566| date=13 February 2015|publisher= Deutschlandradio (DLR Kultur), K\u00f6ln|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis life has been documented in unusual detail, not least by himself.   By 2015 it was reported that the daily diary which he has kept since 1953 had reached its 150th unpublished \"volume\".<ref name=WFlautDLR/>\n\n== Life ==\n=== Childhood and youth ===\nWieland F\u00f6rster was born, the youngest of his parents' four children, in [[:de:Laubegast|Laubegast]], a suburb of [[Dresden]].   His father was employed in the transport and commercial sectors.<ref name=WFlautwww/>    In 1935 his father died as a result of wounds sustained during the [[First World War]], leaving his mother to raise the children under conditions of financial hardship.  She succeeded in distancing them from Nazi indoctrination.   As a school boy, between 1936 and 1944, Wieland rejected the Nazi system and pressures to take part in government sponsored uniformed organisations.   In 1944 he took an apprenticeship as a trainee technical draftsman at the Dresden municipal waterworks.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch|title=Biografie|work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA10| year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9| pages=9\u201317}}</ref>   Towards the end of 1944, still aged only 14, he was sent for four weeks to a [[Hitler Youth]] detention camp.  On his release he volunteered for [[:de:Organisation freiwilliger Luftschutzhelfer|fire-watch duties]] in order to avoid further unwelcome interruptions to his training and education.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL>{{cite web|url=http://das-blaettchen.de/2016/10/franz-fuehmanns-und-wieland-foersters-briefwechsel-37590.html|title=Franz F\u00fchmanns und Wieland F\u00f6rsters Briefwechsel (book review)|date=10 October 2016|author=Peter Liebers|publisher= Das Bl\u00e4ttchen, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt is reported that he was such a quick learner as an apprentice technical draftsmen that after a year he was \"promoted\" to a preparatory year for a degree course at the Engineering Academy.   He was also conscripted into the local branch of the newly launched [[Volkssturm|German Home Guard (''\"Volksturm\"'')]], and it was as a member of the Home Guard that he experienced the [[Bombing of Dresden|English and American air attacks that destroyed the central districts of city]] one day after his fifteenth birthday, on the night of 13 February 1945.<ref name=WFlautDLR/>   In the chaos following the attacks he was able to escape from the Home Guard, remaining in his home district till war ended, formally on 8 May 1945, after which Dresden and the surrounding region of central Germany were [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|administered]] as the [[Soviet occupation]].   Technical draftsmanship was officially designated as women's work, and Wieland was required to undertake hands-on work (''\"als Rohrleger\"'') in industrial engineering.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL/>\n\nOn 17 September 1946 he found himself taken in by the police and handed over to the [[NKVD]] after a neighbour denounced him on grounds of suspected possession of weapons.<ref name=BreifwechsellautPL/>    The background to the affair was an attempt to make the F\u00f6rster family exchange their home for rented accommodation, after the German police had blocked an attempt by the Communist authorities to make them pay rent for living in their own home.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   Wieland was initially sentenced to ten years of forced labour in [[Siberia]], but after three months of nightly interrogation, a Soviet military tribunal reduced the term to 7\u00bd years.   On 28 December 1946 he was interned at [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]], a concentration camp which the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|authorities]] had constructed  next to [[:de:Justizvollzugsanstalt Bautzen|the jail]] at [[Bautzen]].   As the camp commanders set about sorting out the prisoners fit for work to be transported to Siberia, a Soviet military doctor determined that Wieland F\u00f6rster was unfit for work.   He was therefore left behind in [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]].<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In the aftermath of war the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|authorities]] refused to discuss or even to acknowledge the continuing existence of concentration camps in the [[Soviet occupation zone|Soviet part]] of occupied Germany, but their all too physical presence never became increasingly hard to dispute.   By 1950 F\u00f6rster was in poor general health dangerously ill with [[Tuberculosis]] and on 21 January 1950, following a threatened investigation by the [[International Red Cross]], he was the beneficiary of a \"backdoor\" release, emerging from the camp without identity papers and without any formal pardon or other explanation.   Official acknowledgment that he had been a victim of Stalinist persecution followed in 1991.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\n=== Further study and training===\nDespite having emerged from after nearly four years interned in [[NKVD special camps in Germany 1945\u201349|NKVD \"Special Camp\" IV]], in 1950 F\u00f6rster was still aged only 20.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   The previous year, in October 1949, the [[Soviet occupation zone]] had been relaunched as the Soviet sponsored [[German Democratic Republic|German Democratic Republic (East Germany)]].   It was in this new kind of [[one-party state|one-]][[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|party]] [[National Front (East Germany)|dictatorship]],  with its principal [[Constitution of East Germany|political]] and economic structures modelled on those of the [[Soviet Union]] itself, that F\u00f6rster built his life and career over the next four decades.   He abandoned his ambition to become a technical draftsman, but nevertheless returned to work with the Dresden municipal waterworks, employed in the planning department till 1953.<ref name=WFlautGH>{{cite web|url=http://www.galerie-himmel.de/en/Kuenstler/Wieland-Foerster/Vita_2_2.html|title=Wieland F\u00f6rster|publisher=Galerie Himmel, Dresden|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>   During these years he was using his spare time to try out various artistic forms of expression, such as writing, music, theatre and advertising, along with the more visual arts.   In the Autumn/Fall of 1952 he took part in a public \"drawing event\" at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]] where the teachers encouraged him to enroll as a student.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nHe applied to his employers to back his application to sponsor his application to study at [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts|the academy]], but was turned down for reasons that involved the risk of \"Verb\u00fcrgerlichung\" (''loosely: \"bourgeoisization\"'').   He therefore made the application anyway, on his own responsibility, and was accepted.   He was a student at the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]] between 1953 and 1958.<ref name=WFlautwww/>   He began his study of sculpting in 1953, taught by [[Walter Arnold (sculptor)|Walter Arnold]] and Arnold's assistant [[Gerd Jaeger]] .   Another of his teachers was [[Hans Steger (sculptor)|Hans Steger]].   The focus of the training at Dresden was on [[:de:Neoklassizismus (Bildende Kunst)|neoclassical form]], backed up by compulsory courses in drawing, on use of plaster casts and on nature.   The study of anatomy and history of art were also included and required.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nBy his second year F\u00f6rster was already establishing contacts with representatives of the officially forbidden \"classical modern\" art movement.   By this time the [[Iron curtain|division]] [[Allied-occupied Germany|of Germany]] agreed between the [[Allies of World War II|Americans and the Soviets]] at [[Yalta Conference|Yalta]] at the beginning of 1945 had crystallised into  a permanent frontier, but the [[Inner German border|border]] between the two Germanies was still relatively porous, especially between [[West Berlin]] and the surrounding territories governed as [[East Germany]], and F\u00f6rster took the opportunity to visit [[Bernhard Heiliger]] in [[West Berlin|the west]].   [[Walter Arnold (sculptor)|Walter Arnold]], himself a consummate hands-on craftsman, helped a few of his students, whom he regarded as politically reliable, to deepen their understanding on the essential elements in figurative sculpture, by gaining experience with the works of the westerners [[Hermann Haller (sculptor)|Hermann Haller]] and [[Charles Despiau]].<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In his third year, required to produce a \"portrait from a 'photo\", F\u00f6rster chose as his subject [[Bertolt Brecht]], a long-standing icon of the German intellectual left but nevertheless at this stage ostracised by [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|the authorities]].   In order to accomplish his course objective he was permitted, a few weeks before [[Bertolt Brecht|Brecht's]] death in 1956, to attend a rehearsal of [[Life of Galileo]], being staged by the [[Berliner Ensemble|Berliner Ensemble (theatre company)]].<ref name=WFlautZZ>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeitzeugen-tv.com/dossier/movie/4220/wieland-foerster-ein-stiller-rebell.html| title=Wieland F\u00f6rster. Ein stiller Rebell. |publisher=Zeitzeugen Lizenzmanagement (haftungsbeschr\u00e4nkt) UG, Berlin|accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe received his degree in 1958 he applied for a three-year Master Course at the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|Arts Academy in East Berlin]], hoping to study with [[Gustav Seitz]].   However, it was becoming progressively more impractical for Seitz to sustain a life-style that involved pursuing a career simultaneously in [[West German|West]] and [[East Germany]], and 1958 was the year in which he opted to base himself in [[Hamburg]] (in the west).  In order to be able to remain in Berlin, and following the recommendation of Seitz, F\u00f6rster now hesitantly but successfully applied to become a Master Student (''\"Meistersch\u00fcler\"'') with [[Fritz Cremer]].<ref name=WFlautMS>{{cite web |author=Maren Schibilski |url=http://www.rbb-online.de/theodor/archiv/20160619_1832/foerster.html |title=Stiller Rebell - der Bildhauer Wieland F\u00f6rster  |date=19 June 2016 |publisher=Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg (rbb) |accessdate=3 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter just eighteen months his time as a Master Student of [[Fritz Cremer|Cremer]] was prematurely terminated in connection with the increasingly heated debate then emerging on the subject of [[Formalism (art)|Formalism]].   He was permitted to use a workshop at the academy to complete his Life-sized plus group of figures \"V\u00f6lkerfreundschaft unter Studenten\" (literally ''\"People's friendship between students\"'') which won the [[TU Dresden]] prize in 1961/62.<ref name=\"Mlekusch201202\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch|title=Wettbewerbe und Auftraege|work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA75| year=2012| publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9|pages=75\u201384}}</ref>\n\n=== Retreat and recovery ===\nIn 1961 Wieland F\u00f6rster set himself up in a Berlin shop building which became his studio.   For some years he lived and worked here as a virtual hermit, visited by his family and a couple of close friends, notably {{Interlanguage link multi|Erich Arendt|de}} and [[Franz F\u00fchmann]].   The authorities did not endorse his self-imposed exile but nor, at least initially, do they appear to have interfered.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   His only child, Eva F\u00f6rster, was born in Berlin's [[Prenzlauer Berg]] quarter in 1968.   From the time she was six years old her father insisted that she should keep a daily diary, a habit through which she developed a succinct writing style:  she grew up to become a theatre critic, writer and lyricist-poet.<ref name=EFlautSF>{{cite web|url=http://www.eva-foerster.de/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/moz2012.pdf?iframe=true&width=950&height=700|title=Eingefangene Gef\u00fchlsst\u00fcrme:  Keine Eskapaden, keine Skandale \u2013 die Berliner Lyrikerin Eva F\u00f6rster \u00fcber die Arbeit an ihren Gedichten, \u00fcber ihre Inspirationen und Ansichten vom aufregenden Alltagsleben |author=Silvia Fichtner|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>   Between 1968 and 1972, the authorities became disruptive.   F\u00f6rster  was banned from exhibiting his works between 1968 and 1973,<ref name=WFlautwww/> and he was subjected to surveillance techniques that became increasingly intrusive.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>   In the absence of membership of the government approved professional association it became hard to obtain materials, and for some time he operated without an official tax payer reference number.   His perceived attitude in the great [[Formalism (art)|Formalism]] debate and his artistic style earned official condemnation.   In the end, in December 1972, working under conditions of increasing privation from which his health suffered, he was able to arrange an evidently candid meeting with [[Konrad Wolf]], the politically well connected president of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], at which he spelled out his situation.    The timing was propitious, in that the country's new leader, [[Erich Honecker]], was cautiously trying to move the East German government beyond the unrelenting inflexibility of [[Walter Ulbricht|his predecessor]].   The exhibitions ban was lifted, and  F\u00f6rster found himself elected to membership of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]].   More generally, from now on, till the [[Die Wende|demise]] of the East German state in 1989/90, he became a (semi-detached and unconventional) member of the artistic establishment: his relationship with the state now reflected a certain level of mutual acceptance bordering on respect.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\nBetween 1979 and 1990 he served as fifth vice-president, with responsibility for the training of Master Students (''\"Meistersch\u00fcler\"'') at the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]].   In 1985 he was appointed to a professorship.   Since 1991 he has also been a member of [[PEN Centre Germany]].   However, 1991 was also the year in which he resigned from the (formerly ''East'' German) National Arts Academy in protest at the inadequacy of the institution's willingness to investigate and disclose its role under the East German dictatorship.<ref name=WFlautwww/>  Following [[German reunification|reunification]], in 1991 he was obliged to relocate from his 16 M<small>2</small> studio to a small back yard which is where, despite by now suffering from serious heart disease, much of his later work was produced.   For his larger sandstone sculptures he used a piece of land he had acquired (and where he still lives) at [[:de:Wensickendorf|Wensickendorf]] near [[Oranienburg]], to the north of Berlin.<ref name=WFinWensickendorf>{{cite web|url=http://www.maz-online.de/Lokales/Oberhavel/Luther-in-Oranienburg|title=Luther in Oranienburg ... Im Oranienburger Amtshauptmannshaus, hat die Stadt zu Ehren von Wieland F\u00f6rster ein Zimmer eingerichtet. Im Schloss selber gab es keinen ad\u00e4quaten Raum, so B\u00fcrgermeister Hans-Joachim Laesicke.|author=Fritz-Herrmann K\u00f6ser|date=27 April 2014|publisher=M\u00e4rkische Allgemeine (MAZ)|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992<ref name=WFlautGH/><!---There are LOTS of google hits for sites giving this 1992 date, but to my jaundiced eye they all look as though they might very well have been lifted from wikipedia.   And several of the more trusted sites where I would not be surprised to see this mentioned do not, in fact, show it.  So I THINK I prefer 2010 which comes from an entry on the academy's website.   Not able to be 100% certain either way, however.---> or 2010 the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]] took over the Wieland F\u00f6rster Archive, comprising many pages his correspondence with fellow artists and with the authorities in East Germany.<ref name=WFArchiv>{{cite web|date=26 May 2010|title=Akademie der K\u00fcnste erh\u00e4lt das Archiv von Wieland F\u00f6rster| publisher=Akademie der K\u00fcnste |url=http://www.adk.de/de/presse/?we_objectID=25243|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>   In 1996 he was a founding member of the [[S\u00e4chsische Akademie der K\u00fcnste|Saxony Arts Academy]] in [[Dresden]],<ref name=WFlautwww/> to which in 2001 he agreed to donate 58 sculptures.<ref name=\"Mlekusch2012\"/>\n\n== Output ==\nF\u00f6rster was producing lithographic work from 1960.   His first etchings and sculptures for public spaces appeared in 1962.   During the years that followed he took several working trips abroad.   His 1967 stay in [[Tunisia]] was particularly important in influencing his later work.<ref name=\"Mlekusch201203\">{{cite book|author=Monika Mlekusch| title=Vaterlandsschaftung| work=Wieland F\u00f6rster: Werkverzeichnis der Plastiken und Skulpturen| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=it9dfzKHsWsC&pg=PA37|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster| isbn=978-3-643-50402-9|pages=37\u201347}}</ref>   However, foreign travel was a privilege rather than a right, and between 1968 and 1973 governmental agencies imposed various ideologically based blockages including the ban on exhibiting.   Grudging rehabilitation, backed by [[Konrad Wolf]], followed in 1974, when he was admitted to the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], and he was almost immediately able to stage his first major exhibition (organised by {{Interlanguage link multi|Rudolf Tsch\u00e4pe|de}}) in [[Potsdam]] in the former observatory building on the [[Telegrafenberg|Telegraph Hill]].<ref name=RTlautlautBLPB>{{cite web|url=https://www.politische-bildung-brandenburg.de/node/7798|title=Rudolf Tsch\u00e4pe - Ein Portr\u00e4t|date=9 December 2011|work= Pr\u00e4sentation der Videodokumentation auf der Fassade der Gedenkst\u00e4tte Lindenstra\u00dfe 54/55 f\u00fcr die Opfer politischer Gewalt im 20. Jahrhundert |publisher=Dr. Martina Weyrauch i.A. Brandenburgische Landeszentrale f\u00fcr politische Bildung| accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nWieland F\u00f6rster still works as a visual artist.   Additionally, since the 1970s he has published a series of books and articles reflecting aspects of his own artistic creations.<ref name=DNBumWF>{{cite web|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&query=118534173|title=Literatur von und \u00fcber Wieland F\u00f6rster|work=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek |publisher=Deutsche Nationalbibliothek, Frankfurt am Main | accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n''not necessarily a complete list''\n* 1966: [[Will Lammert Prize]] of the German Arts Academy, Berlin\n* 1973: [[Kunstpreis der DDR]]\n* 1974: [[K\u00e4the Kollwitz Prize]] of the [[Academy of Arts, Berlin|National Arts Academy]], Berlin\n* 1976: [[National Prize of the German Democratic Republic]] for arts and literature, 3rd class\n* 1977: Kleist Arts City Prize from [[Frankfurt (Oder)]]\n* 1978: [[:de:Kunstpreis des FDGB|Arts Prize of the Trades Union Confederation]] \n* 1983: [[National Prize of the German Democratic Republic]] for arts and literature, 2nd class\n* 1996: [[:de:Kunstpreis der Landeshauptstadt Dresden|Arts Prize of the Saxon capital, Dresden]]\n* 2000: [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]] 1st class\n* 2009: [[:de:Brandenburgischer Kunstpreis|Brandenburg Arts Prize]] for life's achievement\n* 2010: Honorary doctorate from the Faculty of Philosophy [[Universit\u00e4t Potsdam]]\n* 2012: [[Order of Merit of Brandenburg]]\n\n<!---\n\nIn Bautzen schwor er sich, angesichts der enormen Todesrate zumeist unschuldiger H\u00e4ftlinge, diesen Opfern politischer Willk\u00fcr, in welcher Form auch immer, durch Mahnung und Gedenken ein Weiterleben zu sichern, was er in k\u00fcnstlerischer Form umsetzen wollte.[2] [according to wiki-DE this comes from pages 10-11 of \"source \"Mlekusch2012\" but I can't find it.   Need to look more closely.   It's a nice quote for some purposes.]\n\n--->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:F\u00f6rster, Wieland}}\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:East German artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century German painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:21st-century German sculptors]]\n[[Category:20th-century German printmakers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Victims of human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Prize of East Germany]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wieland_F%C3%B6rster"}
{"title_page": "Uwe Timm", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Uwe Timm (libertarian author)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n | name    = Uwe Timm\n | image   = File:Uwe Timm, Frankfurter Buchmesse 2013 1.jpg\n | image_size = 275px\n | caption = Uwe Timm (2013)\n | birth_name  =\n | birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1940|03|30}}\n | birth_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany\n | residence   = [[Munich]], Berlin\n | death_date  =\n | death_place =\n | occupation  = Writer\n | nationality = German\n | education     = PhD in German literature\n | alma_mater    = Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich\n | spouse        = Dagmar Ploetz\n | children      = four, each of them is dedicated with one novel\n | period   = 1971\u2013present\n | genre    =\n | subject  =\n | movement =\n | notableworks = Am Beispiel meines Bruders, Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel,\n | influences   =\n | influenced   =\n | awards       = {{awd|[[Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Preis]]|2009}} {{awd|[[Deutscher Jugendliteraturpreis]]|1990}}\n}}'''Uwe Timm''' (born 30 March 1940 in [[Hamburg]]) is a German writer.\n\n==Life and work==\n\nUwe Timm was the youngest son in his family. His brother, 16 years his senior, was a soldier in the Waffen SS and died in Ukraine in 1943. Decades later, Uwe Timm approached his relationship with his father and brother in the critically acclaimed novel ''In my brother's shadow''.\n\nAfter working as a furrier, Timm studied Philosophy and German in [[Munich]] and Paris, achieving a PhD in German literature in 1971 with his thesis: ''The Problem of Absurdity in the Works of Albert Camus''. During his studies, Timm was engaged in leftist activities of the 1960s. He became a member of the [[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund|Socialist German Student Union]] and was associated with [[Benno Ohnesorg]]. From 1973 to 1981 he was a member of the [[German Communist Party]]. Three times Timm has been called as a writer-in-residence to several universities in English-speaking countries: in 1981 to the [[University of Warwick]], in 1994 to [[Swansea]] and in 1997 to the [[Washington University in St. Louis]]. He has also been a lecturer at universities in Paderborn, Darmstadt, L\u00fcneburg and Frankfurt.\n\nTimm started publishing in the early 1970s and became known to a larger audience in Germany after one of his children's books, ''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel'', was turned into a movie. Today he is one of the most successful contemporary authors in Germany. His books ''Die Entdeckung der Currywurst ([[The Invention of Curried Sausage]])'' and ''Am Beispiels meines Bruders (In my brother's shadow, or literally: \"By my Brother's Example\")'' can both be found on the syllabi of German schools. His readers usually appreciate Timm's writing style, which he himself calls \"''die \u00c4sthetik des Alltags''\" (\"the aesthetics of everyday life\").<ref>''Erz\u00e4hlen und kein Ende'', A collection of speeches (1993)</ref> Timm imitates everyday storytelling by using everyday vocabulary and simple sentences and generally tries to imitate the way stories are orally told. His works often indirectly link with each other by taking up minor characters from one story and making this character the main character of another work. For example, a minor character like Frau Br\u00fccker from ''Johannisnacht'' is taken up as a main character in his book ''Die Entdeckung der Currywurst''. Timm's works also tend to have autobiographical features and often deal with the German past or are set in the German past.<ref>Hanjo Kersting, Axel Ruckaberle: \"Uwe Timm\", ''Kritisches Lexikon zur deutschsprachigen Gegenwartsliteratur (KLG)'', K\u00f6ln 2004.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*1995 [[Bayerischer Filmpreis|Bavarian Film Award]], Best Young People's Film<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bayern.de/Anlage19170/PreistraegerdesBayerischenFilmpreises-Pierrot.pdf | title=Preistraeger des Bayerischen Filmpreises | accessdate=20 March 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819211539/http://www.bayern.de/Anlage19170/PreistraegerdesBayerischenFilmpreises-Pierrot.pdf | archivedate=19 August 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*1990 [[Deutscher Jugendliteraturpreis]] for ''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel''\n*2009 [[Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Preis]]\n*2012 [[Carl Zuckmayer Medal]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*''Widerspr\u00fcche'', Poems (1971)\n*''Hei\u00dfer Sommer'' (1974)\n*''Wolfenb\u00fcttlerstr. 57'', Poems (1977)\n*''Morenga'' (1978)\n*''Kerbels Flucht'' (1980)\n*''Die deutschen Kolonien'', Photo book (1981)\n*''Die Zugmaus'', Children's book (1981)\n*''Die Piratenamsel'', Children's book (1983)\n*''Der Mann auf dem Hochrad'', Children's book (1984)\n*''Der Schlangenbaum'' (1986)\n*''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel'', Children's book (1989)\n*''Vogel, friss die Feige nicht'' (1989)\n*''Der Kopfj\u00e4ger'' (1991)\n*''Die Piratenamsel'', Children's book (1991)\n*''Erz\u00e4hlen und kein Ende'', A collection of speeches (1993)\n*''Die Entdeckung der Currywurst'' (1993)\n*''Der Schatz auf Pagensand'' (1995)\n*''Johannisnacht'' (1996)\n*''Nicht morgen, nicht gestern'', Short stories (1999)\n*''Rot'', novel (2001), awarded the 2003 [[Schubart-Literaturpreis]]<ref>[[Aalen|City of Aalen]]. [http://www.aalen.de/sixcms/media.php/90/liste_preistraeger_2011.pdf Schubart-Literaturpreis winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504212606/http://www.aalen.de/sixcms/media.php/90/liste_preistraeger_2011.pdf |date=4 May 2012 }}. Retrieved 14 October 2012. {{in lang|de}}</ref>\n*''Am Beispiel meines Bruders'' (2003)\n*''Der Freund und der Fremde'' (2005)\n*''Halbschatten'' (2008)\n*''Freitisch'' (2011)\n*''Vogelweide'' (2013)\n*''Ikarien'' (2017)\n\n===English translations===\n* ''[[The Snake Tree]]'', 1989\n* ''Headhunter'', 1994\n* ''[[The Invention of Curried Sausage]]'', 1995\n* ''Midsummer Nigh''t, 1998\n* ''[[Morenga (novel)|Morenga]]'', 2003\n* ''[[In My Brother's Shadow]]: A Life and Death in the SS'', 2005\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* http://www.dtv.de/_google/autoren/autor21.htm (German)\n* http://www.litrix.de/autoren/autor/uwetimm/enindex.htm\n* David Basker: ''Uwe Timm'', Cardiff 1999 (Contemporary German Writers).\n* Hanjo Kersting, Axel Ruckaberle: \"Uwe Timm\", ''Kritisches Lexikon zur deutschsprachigen Gegenwartsliteratur (KLG)'', K\u00f6ln 2004.\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{German literature}}\n{{Mondello Prize}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timm, Uwe}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Hamburg]]\n[[Category:German Communist Party members]]\n[[Category:Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund members]]\n[[Category:20th-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:German autobiographers]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of the Arts, Berlin]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Uwe Timm (libertarian author)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n | name    = Uwe Timm\n | image   = File:Uwe Timm, Frankfurter Buchmesse 2013 1.jpg\n | image_size = 275px\n | caption = Uwe Timm (2013)\n | birth_name  =\n | birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1940|03|30}}\n | birth_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany\n | residence   = [[Munich]], Berlin\n | death_date  =\n | death_place =\n | occupation  = Writer\n | nationality = German\n | education     = PhD in German literature\n | alma_mater    = Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich\n | spouse        = Dagmar Ploetz\n | children      = four, each of them is dedicated with one novel\n | period   = 1971\u2013present\n | genre    =\n | subject  =\n | movement =\n | notableworks = Am Beispiel meines Bruders, Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel,\n | influences   =\n | influenced   =\n | awards       = {{awd|[[Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Preis]]|2009}} {{awd|[[Deutscher Jugendliteraturpreis]]|1990}}\n}}'''Uwe Timm''' (born 30 March 1940 in [[Hamburg]]) is a German writer.\n\n==Life and work==\n\nUwe Timm was the youngest son in his family. His brother, 16 years his senior, was a soldier in the Waffen SS and died in Ukraine in 1943. Decades later, Uwe Timm approached his relationship with his father and brother in the critically acclaimed novel ''In my brother's shadow''.\n\nAfter working as a furrier, Timm studied Philosophy and German in [[Munich]] and Paris, achieving a PhD in German literature in 1971 with his thesis: ''The Problem of Absurdity in the Works of Albert Camus''. During his studies, Timm was engaged in leftist activities of the 1960s. He became a member of the [[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund|Socialist German Student Union]] and was associated with [[Benno Ohnesorg]]. From 1973 to 1981 he was a member of the [[German Communist Party]]. Three times Timm has been called as a writer-in-residence to several universities in English-speaking countries: in 1981 to the [[University of Warwick]], in 1994 to [[Swansea]] and in 1997 to the [[Washington University in St. Louis]]. He has also been a lecturer at universities in Paderborn, Darmstadt, L\u00fcneburg and Frankfurt.\n\nTimm started publishing in the early 1970s and became known to a larger audience in Germany after one of his children's books, ''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel'', was turned into a movie. Today he is one of the most successful contemporary authors in Germany. His books ''Die Entdeckung der Currywurst ([[The Invention of Curried Sausage]])'' and ''Am Beispiels meines Bruders (In my brother's shadow, or literally: \"By my Brother's Example\")'' can both be found on the syllabi of German schools. His readers usually appreciate Timm's writing style, which he himself calls \"''die \u00c4sthetik des Alltags''\" (\"the aesthetics of everyday life\").<ref>''Erz\u00e4hlen und kein Ende'', A collection of speeches (1993)</ref> Timm imitates everyday storytelling by using everyday vocabulary and simple sentences and generally tries to imitate the way stories are orally told. His works often indirectly link with each other by taking up minor characters from one story and making this character the main character of another work. For example, a minor character like Frau Br\u00fccker from ''Johannisnacht'' is taken up as a main character in his book ''Die Entdeckung der Currywurst''. Timm's works also tend to have autobiographical features and often deal with the German past or are set in the German past.<ref>Hanjo Kersting, Axel Ruckaberle: \"Uwe Timm\", ''Kritisches Lexikon zur deutschsprachigen Gegenwartsliteratur (KLG)'', K\u00f6ln 2004.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*1995 [[Bayerischer Filmpreis|Bavarian Film Award]], Best Young People's Film<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bayern.de/Anlage19170/PreistraegerdesBayerischenFilmpreises-Pierrot.pdf | title=Preistraeger des Bayerischen Filmpreises | accessdate=20 March 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819211539/http://www.bayern.de/Anlage19170/PreistraegerdesBayerischenFilmpreises-Pierrot.pdf | archivedate=19 August 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*1990 [[Deutscher Jugendliteraturpreis]] for ''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcssel''\n*2009 [[Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Preis]]\n*2012 [[Carl Zuckmayer Medal]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n*''Widerspr\u00fcche'', Poems (1971)\n*''Hei\u00dfer Sommer'' (1974)\n*''Wolfenb\u00fcttlerstr. 57'', Poems (1977)\n*''Morenga'' (1978)\n*''Kerbels Flucht'' (1980)\n*''Die deutschen Kolonien'', Photo book (1981)\n*''Die Zugmaus'', Children's book (1981)\n*''Die Piratenamsel'', Children's book (1983)\n*''Der Mann auf dem Hochrad'', Children's book (1984)\n*''Der Schlangenbaum'' (1986)\n*''Rennschwein Rudi R\u00fcsse